/* Deer School — Question Bank */
const QUESTION_BANK = [
  // BATCH 1 — Biology Q1-Q30
  {category:"Biology",question:"When observing a herd during the spring transition from winter to summer coats, which demographic of deer is typically the last to complete the moult?",options:["Females","Old deer","Young deer","Males"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Older deer have slower metabolisms and physical responses, so they are normally the last to shed their winter coat and transition into their summer coat."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"Amongst male antlered deer, which individuals are usually the first to cast (shed) their antlers each year?",options:["Yearlings","Kids/Calves","Old animals","Those with a perruque head"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"The oldest, most mature males cast their antlers first, allowing them the longest possible growing season to develop a new set for the following rut."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"What is the typical behaviour of a female deer when she is preparing to give birth?",options:["She remains in the middle of the herd for protection","She seeks high, open ground to watch for predators","She isolates herself quietly in cover","She keeps the male close by for defense"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"To protect her highly vulnerable newborn from predators, a female deer will separate from the herd and give birth quietly and alone in thick cover."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"The annual cycle of antler casting and regrowth is primarily controlled by which hormone?",options:["Testosterone","Adrenaline","Progesterone","Oestrogen"],correctIndex:0,explanation:"Testosterone governs the antler cycle. A drop in testosterone causes the antlers to cast, while rising levels cause the velvet to shed and the antlers to harden."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"How do newborn deer typically behave during their first few days of life?",options:["They are left alone in cover by their mothers between suckling bouts","They follow their mothers closely within an hour of birth","They gather together in nursery groups","They immediately move to low ground"],correctIndex:0,explanation:"Newborns rely on camouflage and being scentless. They lie completely still in cover while the mother grazes elsewhere, returning only briefly to let them suckle."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"What is the primary physical requirement a female deer must achieve before she is capable of conceiving?",options:["She must be at least 4 years old","She must reach a certain threshold body weight","She must establish her own home range","She must be mated by multiple males"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Conception is largely dependent on body condition. If a female does not reach a specific threshold body weight, she will not ovulate or conceive."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"What is the ultimate, primary limiting factor for the natural lifespan of a wild deer?",options:["The physical strain of the rut","Loss of territory","Its teeth wearing out so it cannot feed efficiently","Predation by other deer"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"A deer's life is ultimately limited by its teeth. Once their teeth wear down to the point they can no longer grind tough forage efficiently, they cannot extract enough nutrition to survive."},
  {category:"Disease & Management",question:"If you observe a male deer with a perruque head (a spongy, continuously growing mass of velvet), what is the correct management action?",options:["It should be protected as valuable breeding stock","It should be culled as the velvet will likely become infected, leading to its death","It should be left alone, as it will naturally harden soon","It must not be shot under any circumstances"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"A perruque head never sheds its velvet due to a lack of testosterone. It will grow uncontrollably over the eyes and become fatally infected, so the animal must be culled on welfare grounds."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"Why is it biologically necessary for deer to ruminate (chew the cud)?",options:["It is a reaction to stress","It helps them rest and cool down","It is essential to their digestion","It sharpens their lower teeth"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Deer are ruminants. Regurgitating and re-chewing their food is an essential biological process required to break down tough plant cellulose so it can be properly digested."},
  {category:"Identification",question:"Which two deer species are truly native to the United Kingdom?",options:["Red and Sika","Roe and Fallow","Red and Roe","Muntjac and Chinese Water Deer"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Only Red deer and Roe deer are native. Fallow were introduced by the Normans, while Sika, Muntjac, and CWD are more recent introductions."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"At what time of year do Roe deer rut?",options:["Late Autumn","Mid-Summer (July/August)","Early Spring","Deep Winter"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Roe deer are unique among UK deer species as they rut in mid-summer. Other species like Red, Fallow, and Sika rut in the autumn."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"What unique reproductive trait occurs in Roe does after the summer rut?",options:["Delayed implantation","They give birth in the winter","They breed twice a year","They reject the bucks entirely"],correctIndex:0,explanation:"Following fertilization in the summer, the embryo floats freely in the uterus and does not implant until late December or early January."},
  {category:"Identification",question:"Which species of deer lacks a visible tail and has a prominent white rump patch that flares out when alarmed?",options:["Sika","Muntjac","Chinese Water Deer","Roe Deer"],correctIndex:3,explanation:"Roe deer have a highly visible white or yellowish rump patch that flares in response to danger, and they lack a distinct tail."},
  {category:"Identification",question:"What distinguishes a mature Fallow buck's antlers from other UK deer species?",options:["They never shed their velvet","They grow straight backwards like spikes","They are broad, flattened, and palmate","They point exclusively forward"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Mature Fallow bucks develop distinct palmate (flattened and broad) antlers, unique among UK deer."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"Which UK deer species has no defined breeding season and can produce young throughout the entire year?",options:["Roe Deer","Muntjac","Sika","Red Deer"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Muntjac breed continuously year-round, meaning they have no statutory closed season."},
  {category:"Identification",question:"Which deer species is characterized by the presence of prominent upper canine tusks in males, and a total lack of antlers?",options:["Muntjac","Sika","Chinese Water Deer","Roe"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Chinese Water Deer do not grow antlers; instead, males defend territories using their long upper canine tusks."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"What is the typical gestation period for a Red deer hind?",options:["5 months","6 months","8 months","11 months"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"The gestation period for a Red hind is approximately 8 months, meaning calves conceived in October are born around June."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"What term is used to describe the aggressive rubbing of antlers on trees or bushes by male deer?",options:["Browsing","Fraying","Wallowing","Thrashing"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Fraying is the process where males aggressively rub their newly hardened antlers against vegetation to strip the velvet and leave scent markers."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"What is the function of the interdigital glands on a deer?",options:["To produce tears","To mark twigs and branches at eye level","To leave a scent trail on the ground from between the hooves","To regulate body temperature"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Located between the hooves, the interdigital glands secrete a scent that leaves a trail on the ground as the deer walks."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"When does a mature Roe buck typically cast its antlers?",options:["March to April","November to December","July to August","May to June"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Unlike Red and Fallow deer which cast in the spring, Roe bucks cast their antlers in early winter (November/December)."},
  {category:"Identification",question:"Which deer species communicates danger using a repetitive, sharp bark that sounds similar to a fox?",options:["Red Deer","Muntjac","Sika","Fallow"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Muntjac are highly vocal when alarmed and will emit a loud, sharp bark repeatedly from the cover of undergrowth."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"What does the term 'browse line' refer to?",options:["The specific trail a herd follows","The maximum height that deer can reach to eat leaves and shoots from trees","The territorial boundary of a dominant male","The line of fresh grass growing near a river"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"A browse line is the visible, horizontal line in woodland foliage created when deer consume all the reachable leaves and twigs from the ground up."},
  {category:"Identification",question:"Which UK deer species displays a stark white, heart-shaped rump patch with a sharp black upper border?",options:["Sika","Roe","Fallow","Muntjac"],correctIndex:0,explanation:"Sika deer have a very distinct, bright white heart-shaped rump patch bordered by black hair."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"Why do Red stags and Sika stags create muddy wallows during the rut?",options:["To hide from stalkers","To escape biting insects","To roll in mud and their own urine, darkening their coat and spreading their scent","To find roots to eat"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Wallowing coats the stag in mud and urine, which acts as a powerful scent marker and visual display to intimidate rivals and attract females."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"How many upper incisor teeth does a healthy adult deer have?",options:["Two","Four","Zero","Six"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Deer have zero upper incisors. They have a hard dental pad on the upper jaw against which the lower incisors press to tear vegetation."},
  {category:"Identification",question:"Which of the following describes the Menil variation of a Fallow deer?",options:["Almost completely black","A pale, heavily spotted coat that retains its spots prominently throughout the winter","Pure white all over","A standard brown coat with no spots"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"The Menil coat is paler than the common Fallow and distinctly retains its white spots all year round."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"What material actually constitutes the hard antler of a deer?",options:["Compressed hair","Solid bone","Cartilage","Keratin"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Unlike the horns of sheep or cattle (which are keratin), a deer's antlers are made of true, rapidly growing bone."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"Which UK deer species is known to interbreed (hybridize) with native Red deer, threatening the genetic purity of the Red population?",options:["Fallow","Roe","Muntjac","Sika"],correctIndex:3,explanation:"Sika deer belong to the same genus (Cervus) as Red deer, and will readily crossbreed where their populations overlap."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"What is the pre-orbital gland used for?",options:["Digesting tough bark","Marking twigs and vegetation with scent","Cleaning the eyes","Regulating body temperature"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Located just in front of the eye, the pre-orbital gland secretes fluid used to scent-mark branches and assert territory."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"What environmental factor is the primary trigger for the onset of the autumn rut in Red, Fallow, and Sika deer?",options:["Dropping temperatures","The first frost","Decreasing daylight hours (photoperiodism)","Heavy rainfall"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"The shortening of daylight hours in late summer and early autumn triggers hormonal changes (increased testosterone) that initiate the rut."},

  // BATCH 2 — Legislation Q31-Q42 + Safety Q43-Q52 + Ballistics Q53-Q60
  {category:"Legislation",question:"In England and Wales, what is the minimum legal calibre and muzzle energy required to shoot Red, Fallow, and Sika deer?",options:[".222 inches and 1000 ft/lbs",".240 inches and 1700 ft/lbs",".270 inches and 2000 ft/lbs",".308 inches and 2400 ft/lbs"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"For the larger deer species in England and Wales, the law requires a minimum calibre of .240 inches and a minimum muzzle energy of 1,700 foot-pounds."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"Under Scottish law, what are the minimum legal requirements to shoot Red, Fallow, and Sika deer?",options:["Bullet weight 80 grains, muzzle velocity 2,450 fps, muzzle energy 1,750 ft/lbs","Bullet weight 50 grains, muzzle energy 1,000 ft/lbs","Calibre .240 inches, muzzle energy 1,700 ft/lbs","There are no specific minimums in Scotland"],correctIndex:0,explanation:"Scotland specifies three metrics for large deer: the bullet must weigh at least 80 grains (reduced from 100gr in November 2023), travel at 2,450 fps, and generate 1,750 ft/lbs of muzzle energy."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"Under Scottish law, what are the minimum legal requirements to shoot Roe deer?",options:["100 grains, 1,750 ft/lbs","50 grains, 2,450 fps, 1,000 ft/lbs",".240 calibre, 1,700 ft/lbs",".222 calibre, 1,500 ft/lbs"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"For Roe deer in Scotland, the bullet must weigh at least 50 grains, with a minimum muzzle velocity of 2,450 fps and a minimum muzzle energy of 1,000 ft/lbs."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"In England and Wales, what is the minimum legal requirement to shoot Roe, Muntjac, and Chinese Water Deer?",options:["Calibre .240, 1,700 ft/lbs","Calibre .220, bullet weight 50 grains, muzzle energy 1,000 ft/lbs","Calibre .17 HMR, muzzle energy 500 ft/lbs","Calibre .22LR, bullet weight 40 grains"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"For the three smaller species in England and Wales, you must use a minimum calibre of .220, a bullet weighing at least 50 grains, and generating 1,000 ft/lbs of muzzle energy."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"What type of ammunition is legally required for shooting deer in the UK?",options:["Full Metal Jacket (FMJ)","Armour Piercing","Expanding ammunition (e.g., soft-point or ballistic tip)","Solid brass solids"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"The Deer Act requires the use of expanding ammunition, which deforms upon impact to transfer energy and ensure a humane dispatch."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"Is it legal to shoot deer at night in the UK?",options:["Yes, if you use a thermal scope","Yes, but only for Muntjac","No, it is an offence unless operating under a specific night-shooting licence","Yes, on private land with the owner's permission"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Shooting deer at night (defined as one hour after sunset to one hour before sunrise) is illegal without a specific licence, usually only granted to prevent serious damage."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"Under what specific exemption can a smooth-bore shotgun be legally used to shoot a deer?",options:["For sport in dense woodland","To humanely dispatch a severely injured deer, or to prevent serious agricultural damage under strict conditions","When a rifle is broken","Shotguns are completely illegal for deer under all circumstances"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"While generally banned for sport, shotguns may be used as a last resort to dispatch a suffering deer, or by farmers under strict exemptions to prevent serious crop damage."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"Is it legal to shoot a deer from a moving vehicle?",options:["Yes, if driving below 10 mph","Yes, on private land","No, it is strictly illegal; the vehicle must be stationary and the engine turned off","Yes, if shooting out the passenger window"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Shooting from a moving vehicle is highly dangerous and explicitly illegal. The vehicle must be stationary and the engine off before firing."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"Who holds the legal authority to grant you permission to shoot deer on a specific piece of land?",options:["The local police Firearms Enquiry Officer","The landowner or the person holding the legal shooting/sporting rights","The British Deer Society","The local parish council"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Only the individual or entity that owns the sporting rights (usually the landowner or a syndicate) can grant lawful permission to stalk deer on that land."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"In England and Wales, what is the open season for Red Stags?",options:["1st August to 30th April","1st November to 31st March","1st April to 31st October","There is no closed season"],correctIndex:0,explanation:"The male open season for Red, Fallow, and Sika in England and Wales runs from 1st August to 30th April."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"In England and Wales, what is the open season for Roe Bucks?",options:["1st November to 31st March","1st April to 31st October","1st August to 30th April","1st July to 20th October"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Roe Bucks in England and Wales are in season from 1st April to 31st October."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"In England and Wales, what is the open season for Roe Does?",options:["1st April to 31st October","1st November to 31st March","1st August to 30th April","1st September to 28th February"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Roe Does (along with Red Hinds, Fallow Does, and Sika Hinds) are in season during the winter months, from 1st November to 31st March in England and Wales."},
  {category:"Safety",question:"Before taking a shot, what must you absolutely guarantee exists directly behind the deer?",options:["A clear line of sight for 1000 meters","A body of water","A safe, solid backstop (such as soft earth or a rising bank) to safely catch the bullet","A thick hedge or line of trees"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Hunting bullets frequently pass completely through a deer. You must have a solid earth backstop to trap the exiting bullet safely."},
  {category:"Safety",question:"Why must you never shoot at a deer standing on the skyline?",options:["The deer will see you too easily","The wind is unpredictable","There is no safe backstop; a missed or pass-through bullet will travel over the hill with lethal force into unknown territory","The sun will glare in the scope"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"A skylined shot is inherently dangerous because you cannot see where the bullet will land on the other side of the hill."},
  {category:"Safety",question:"When stalking alone, what is the correct procedure for crossing a fence or deep ditch with your rifle?",options:["Keep the safety on and jump over","Sling the rifle securely over your back and climb","Unload the rifle, open the bolt, safely place the rifle on the other side, cross the obstacle, and retrieve it","Hand it over the fence first while keeping it loaded"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Never cross an obstacle holding a firearm or with a loaded weapon. Always unload, make safe, place the weapon through the obstacle, cross, and retrieve."},
  {category:"Safety",question:"How must ammunition legally be stored at home?",options:["In the rifle's magazine for quick access","In a separate, secure, lockable compartment or safe away from the firearms","On a high shelf out of reach of children","In your vehicle's glovebox"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Firearms law dictates that ammunition must be kept securely locked up, and strictly in a separate compartment from the firearms themselves."},
  {category:"Safety",question:"You squeeze the trigger on a deer, but the rifle only goes 'click'. What is your immediate action?",options:["Quickly cycle the bolt to load the next round","Look down the barrel to check for a blockage","Keep the rifle pointed at the safe backstop and wait at least 30 seconds in case of a 'hang-fire', then safely unload","Shake the rifle and try pulling the trigger again"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"A hang-fire is a delayed detonation of the primer or powder. Opening the bolt immediately could result in the cartridge exploding in your face."},
  {category:"Safety",question:"What is the safest way to get your rifle into a high seat?",options:["Climb with the loaded rifle slung over your back","Climb with the rifle in one hand","Unload the rifle, climb into the seat, and use a haul rope to carefully pull the unloaded rifle up to you","Leave it at the bottom until you see a deer"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Climbing a ladder with a rifle is dangerous. You should always use a haul cord to lift an unloaded rifle into the seat once you are stable."},
  {category:"Safety",question:"When transporting a rifle in a vehicle on public roads, how should it be stored?",options:["Loaded but with the safety catch on","Unloaded, in a securely fastened slip or hard case, ideally out of sight, with the bolt and ammunition stored separately","Unloaded but visible in the window","Loaded and kept in the boot"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"To comply with the law and prevent theft, firearms must be unloaded, out of sight, and practically inaccessible to unauthorized persons during transport."},
  {category:"Safety",question:"When walking alongside a companion during a stalk, what is the golden rule regarding your rifle?",options:["Always keep the safety catch on","Keep the bolt closed to keep dirt out","The rifle must be unloaded, and you must maintain strict muzzle awareness so the barrel never points at your companion","The person in front carries the loaded rifle"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Muzzle awareness is the cornerstone of safety. A rifle should be unloaded when moving with others, and the muzzle must always point in a safe direction."},
  {category:"Safety",question:"If you slip and your rifle muzzle gets pushed into the mud, what must you do before firing?",options:["Wipe the outside of the barrel with your sleeve","Fire a 'clearing shot' into the ground","Unload the rifle, remove the bolt, and visually inspect the bore to ensure it is completely free of obstructions","Turn the safety catch on and off"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Even a small plug of mud or snow in the barrel can cause a catastrophic pressure spike when fired, resulting in the barrel exploding."},
  {category:"Safety",question:"To what extent can you rely on a rifle's mechanical safety catch?",options:["Completely, as long as the rifle is modern","You should never rely solely on a safety catch; it is a mechanical device that can fail. The only true safety is an unloaded chamber and safe muzzle direction","Only when crossing obstacles","It is 100% reliable if serviced annually"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Safety catches fail, slip, or get snagged on twigs. Safe muzzle handling and unloading when appropriate are the only guarantees of safety."},
  {category:"Ballistics",question:"What causes a bullet to ricochet?",options:["Shooting in heavy rain","The bullet striking a hard, flat, or frozen surface at a shallow angle, causing it to bounce unpredictably","Using a bullet that is too heavy","A dirty rifle barrel"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Ricochets occur when the bullet fails to penetrate a surface and instead deflects off it, remaining lethal for a considerable distance."},
  {category:"Ballistics",question:"What does the term 'trajectory' refer to in rifle shooting?",options:["The speed of the bullet","The curved flight path of the bullet as it drops over distance due to gravity","The expansion of the bullet in the target","The spin imparted by the rifling"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"A bullet does not travel in a straight line; gravity pulls it down as soon as it leaves the muzzle, creating a curved trajectory."},
  {category:"Ballistics",question:"What is the process of 'zeroing' a rifle?",options:["Cleaning the barrel completely","Adjusting the telescopic sights so that the bullet's point of impact aligns exactly with the crosshairs at a specific known distance","Emptying the magazine safely","Shooting point-blank into a target"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Zeroing matches your line of sight to the bullet's trajectory at a chosen range (e.g., 100 meters)."},
  {category:"Ballistics",question:"If you shoot at a deer at a very steep upward or downward angle, how will the bullet strike compared to shooting on flat ground?",options:["It will strike lower","It will strike exactly the same","It will strike higher than expected","It will drift horizontally"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Gravity acts on the horizontal distance to the target. At steep angles, the horizontal distance is shorter, so the bullet drops less and hits high."},
  {category:"Ballistics",question:"What is meant by 'Maximum Point Blank Range' (MPBR)?",options:["Shooting at a target touching the muzzle","The maximum distance at which the bullet's trajectory neither rises nor falls outside the vital kill zone, allowing you to aim dead-center","The distance a bullet can travel before hitting the ground","The range at which the bullet loses all energy"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"MPBR allows a stalker to hold the crosshairs dead center on the chest without adjusting for drop, knowing the bullet will stay within a 4-to-6-inch lethal circle."},
  {category:"Ballistics",question:"How does a strong crosswind affect a bullet's flight?",options:["It pushes the bullet laterally in the direction the wind is blowing (wind drift)","It slows the bullet down, causing it to hit low","It makes the bullet tumble","It speeds the bullet up"],correctIndex:0,explanation:"Wind exerts pressure on the side of the bullet, causing it to drift off the point of aim. A left-to-right wind will push the bullet to the right."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"What does an 'Open' condition on a Firearm Certificate (FAC) allow the holder to do?",options:["Shoot at night","Use any calibre of rifle","Shoot over any land where they have lawful permission, without needing the police to inspect and approve the land first","Shoot without a safe backstop"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"An 'Open' ticket means the police trust the holder's experience to assess land safety themselves, rather than restricting them to specific, pre-cleared parcels of land."},
  {category:"Safety",question:"What is the primary health and safety benefit of using a sound moderator?",options:["It makes the rifle completely silent","It drastically reduces the muzzle blast at the shooter's ear, preventing permanent cumulative hearing damage, and reduces recoil","It increases bullet velocity","It ensures the deer doesn't hear the shot"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Moderators do not silence supersonic bullets (which still produce a loud 'crack'), but they do suppress the explosive muzzle blast, protecting the shooter's hearing."},

  // BATCH 3 — Meat Hygiene Q61-Q80 + Fieldcraft Q81-Q90
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"In the context of wild game meat hygiene, what is the primary role of a 'Trained Person'?",options:["To butcher the carcass into retail cuts","To inspect the carcass and its viscera (organs) immediately after shooting to ensure there are no signs of disease or contamination","To transport the meat to the dealer","To cook the meat for public consumption"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"The Trained Person's legal responsibility is to conduct a primary field inspection of the carcass and organs to ensure it is fit to enter the human food chain."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"If you intend to sell a whole, in-skin deer carcass to an Approved Game Handling Establishment (AGHE), what documentation MUST be attached to it?",options:["A copy of your Firearm Certificate","A photograph of the shot site","A completed Hunter's Declaration signed by a 'Trained Person'","A veterinary certificate"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"An AGHE cannot legally accept a carcass for the commercial food chain unless it is accompanied by a signed declaration from a Trained Person stating no abnormalities were found."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"Which of the following is classed as a 'Notifiable Disease' in the UK?",options:["Lyme Disease","Liver Fluke","Foot and Mouth Disease","Lungworm"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Foot and Mouth Disease, Anthrax, and Bovine Tuberculosis are Notifiable Diseases. They pose massive risks to agriculture and public health."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"If you shoot a deer and suspect it is suffering from a Notifiable Disease, what is your immediate legal obligation?",options:["Bury the carcass deep in the woods","Notify the Animal and Plant Health Agency (APHA) or the Police immediately, and do not move the carcass","Cut away the diseased parts and sell the rest","Burn the carcass on site"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"By law, suspected Notifiable Diseases must be reported immediately to the authorities, and the carcass must remain strictly quarantined in place to prevent spreading the infection."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"You observe a deer with blisters and painful ulcers on its tongue, lips, and around its hooves. Which Notifiable Disease do these symptoms strongly suggest?",options:["Bovine Tuberculosis","Foot and Mouth Disease","Anthrax","Rabies"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Blisters and ulcerated lesions on the mouth, snout, and feet are the classic, highly contagious symptoms of Foot and Mouth Disease."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"You find a deer that has died suddenly. Dark, tar-like blood that does not clot is oozing from its nose and anus. Which Notifiable Disease should you suspect?",options:["Anthrax","Tuberculosis","Chronic Wasting Disease","E. coli"],correctIndex:0,explanation:"Sudden death accompanied by dark, uncoagulated blood leaking from the body's orifices is the primary indicator of Anthrax, which is highly dangerous to humans."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"During the gralloch, you inspect the lymph nodes and lungs and find hard, gritty, yellowish pus-filled lumps. What disease does this indicate?",options:["Bovine Tuberculosis","Liver fluke","Ticks","Bluetongue"],correctIndex:0,explanation:"Tuberculosis typically presents as hard, calcified, or pus-filled lesions (tubercles) in the lungs and the lymph nodes of the head and chest."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"Where are the retropharyngeal and submaxillary lymph nodes located?",options:["Attached to the stomach","In the head and under the jaw","In the hind legs","Between the lungs"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"These lymph nodes are located in the head and throat area. Inspecting them is a key requirement of the Trained Person examination, particularly for signs of TB."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"Where are the mesenteric lymph nodes located?",options:["In the neck","In the mesentery web attached to the intestines and stomach","Behind the knee joint","Along the spine"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"The mesenteric lymph nodes are found within the thin, web-like tissue (the mesentery) that supports the digestive tract."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"What is the primary hygiene reason for 'bleeding' a deer as soon as possible after shooting?",options:["To make the carcass lighter to carry","To prevent blood from pooling in the muscle tissue, which promotes rapid bacterial growth and spoils the meat","To attract scavengers to the site","To make skinning easier"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Blood is an ideal breeding ground for bacteria. Draining it quickly cools the carcass and significantly improves the quality and shelf life of the venison."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"When inspecting the kidneys of a normal, healthy deer, what should the surrounding fat look like?",options:["Yellow and liquid","Firm, hard, and white","Translucent, watery, and jelly-like","Non-existent"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"A healthy deer will store firm, white suet fat around its kidneys. This fat is a prime indicator of the animal's overall condition."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"If the fat surrounding the kidneys and heart is translucent, watery, and jelly-like, what does this indicate?",options:["The deer is in peak physical condition","The deer was pregnant","The deer has suffered from severe malnutrition, starvation, or chronic disease","The meat is exceptionally tender"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"When a deer is starving or battling severe chronic illness, it consumes its own fat reserves. The remaining fat turns into a watery, gelatinous state."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"During the gralloch, you accidentally puncture the rumen and green matter spills onto the meat. How must you clean it?",options:["Wash it out thoroughly with water from a nearby stream","Wipe it off with a handful of grass or a rag","Carefully trim away and discard all the contaminated meat using a clean knife","Leave it alone; cooking will fix it"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Washing a carcass with water spreads bacterial contamination everywhere. The only hygienic method is to cut away the affected meat and discard it."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"What is 'bone taint'?",options:["A disease of the bone marrow","Deep bacterial putrefaction and souring of the meat around the large bones caused by the carcass cooling too slowly","A chemical used to clean deer skulls","A type of fly strike"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"If a carcass is not cooled adequately, the thick layers of muscle insulate the deep joints, allowing bacteria to multiply rapidly in the warm, deep tissue, ruining the meat."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"What is 'cold shortening'?",options:["A method of aging meat in a fridge","When a carcass is chilled too rapidly before rigor mortis sets in, causing muscle fibers to contract violently and permanently toughen the meat","When deer lose weight in winter","When the legs shrink during cooking"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Carcasses must be cooled steadily. If plunged into aggressive chilling (below 10°C too quickly), cold shortening occurs, making the venison incredibly tough and unpalatable."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"What is the maximum legally permitted core temperature for a large wild game carcass prior to being transported to an AGHE?",options:["0 degrees Celsius","4 degrees Celsius","7 degrees Celsius","12 degrees Celsius"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Food hygiene regulations state that large wild game must be chilled to an internal core temperature of 7°C or below before entering the AGHE chain."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"What is the most effective field method to prevent cross-contamination when switching between cutting the dirty exterior and the clean interior meat?",options:["Using the 'two-knife system' (one knife for dirty work, one strictly for clean work)","Wiping your single knife on your trousers","Rinsing your knife in a puddle","Working as fast as possible"],correctIndex:0,explanation:"Using two separate knives (or thoroughly sanitizing one knife between stages) ensures bacteria from the skin and feces are not transferred to the sterile meat."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"Which zoonotic disease is commonly transmitted to humans via the bite of an infected sheep tick?",options:["Bovine TB","Foot and Mouth Disease","Lyme Disease","Rabies"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Lyme disease is a serious bacterial infection carried by ticks. Stalkers should check themselves for ticks regularly and look out for the 'bullseye' rash."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"Where would you typically find the larvae of the Warble Fly on a deer carcass?",options:["In the liver","In the nasal passages","Buried in small cysts just beneath the skin along the deer's back","In the lungs"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Warble fly larvae migrate through the body and form lumps under the skin on the back, where they breathe through a small hole, damaging the hide and local meat."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"When inspecting the liver, you notice flat, leaf-shaped parasites in the bile ducts. What are these?",options:["Liver flukes","Lungworms","Tapeworms","Nasal bots"],correctIndex:0,explanation:"Liver flukes infect the liver's bile ducts. While the affected parts of the liver must be discarded, the meat of the carcass is generally still safe for consumption."},
  {category:"Fieldcraft",question:"Immediately after firing at a deer, what should your first action be?",options:["Stand up and walk toward the deer","Lower the rifle and celebrate","Cycle the bolt to load a fresh round while keeping the rifle aimed at the deer, and observe its reaction through the scope","Put the safety catch on and unload"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"You must always be prepared for an immediate follow-up shot. Reloading instantly without taking your eye off the target ensures you are ready if the deer is not lethally hit."},
  {category:"Fieldcraft",question:"Upon inspecting the shot site where a deer was standing, you find bright pink, frothy blood containing bubbles. What does this indicate?",options:["A liver shot","A gut shot","A heart/lung shot","A leg wound"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Pink, frothy blood mixed with air bubbles is the classic sign of a lethal strike to the lungs."},
  {category:"Fieldcraft",question:"At the shot site, you find thick, dark red or crimson blood. What does this indicate?",options:["A lung shot","A strike to the liver or a major vein","A clean miss","A high neck shot"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Dark, heavy blood usually indicates a venous bleed or a liver shot. The animal is fatally wounded but may travel further."},
  {category:"Fieldcraft",question:"You shoot a deer, but at the strike site you find stomach contents, green/brown fluid, and a foul smell. What is the correct action?",options:["Run after it immediately","Wait approximately 45 minutes to an hour before following up","Wait until the next morning","Abandon the stalk"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"A gut-shot deer will die, but it may take hours. If pushed immediately, it will run for miles. Waiting an hour allows it to bed down."},
  {category:"Fieldcraft",question:"While tracking, you find a piece of shattered white bone and clear, jelly-like fluid. What does this indicate?",options:["A heart shot","A liver shot","A non-lethal strike to a leg joint","A spine shot"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Bone fragments accompanied by synovial (joint) fluid indicate a leg shot. The deer is highly mobile but severely injured."},
  {category:"Fieldcraft",question:"You take a shot, and the deer drops instantly. However, its head remains up and it appears to be trying to pull itself forward with its front legs. What has happened?",options:["It is a perfect heart shot","The bullet has struck high in the spine; the animal is paralyzed in the rear but fully conscious and suffering","The deer simply tripped in shock","The bullet missed but the noise stunned it"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"An instant drop with the head remaining up usually indicates a central nervous system (spine) hit that missed the brain. The animal requires immediate dispatch."},
  {category:"Fieldcraft",question:"You find a patch of long, coarse, bright white hair at the shot site. What does this suggest?",options:["It was a perfect chest shot","The shot was too high","The shot was very low, likely grazing the brisket or the belly","It was a neck shot"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Long, bright white hair on most UK deer species originates from the belly or lower brisket area, indicating the shot was placed too low."},
  {category:"Fieldcraft",question:"Before beginning a stalk, what is the most critical environmental factor a stalker must check to avoid being detected?",options:["The temperature","The wind direction","The phase of the moon","The barometric pressure"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Deer rely primarily on their acute sense of smell. You must always stalk into the wind (wind blowing from the deer towards you) or across the wind."},
  {category:"Fieldcraft",question:"If you suspect you have hit a deer in the heart or lungs, but it runs out of sight, how long should you generally wait before following up?",options:["Follow up immediately at a sprint","Wait 10 to 15 minutes","Wait 1 hour","Wait until dusk"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Even with a destroyed heart, a deer has enough oxygen in its brain to run for several seconds. Waiting 10-15 minutes allows it to expire peacefully."},
  {category:"Fieldcraft",question:"What is the primary visual difference between a roe deer's summer coat and its winter coat?",options:["The summer coat is thick and grey, the winter coat is bright red","The summer coat is rusty reddish-brown, while the winter coat is thick, coarse, and grey-brown","There is no colour difference","The summer coat has white spots, the winter coat does not"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Roe deer moult twice a year. Their summer coat is a distinct foxy reddish-brown, which they shed in autumn for a dense, insulating grey-brown winter coat."},

  // BATCH 4 — Identification Q91-Q100 + Legislation Q101-Q120
  {category:"Identification",question:"Which of the following represents the four recognized coat colour variations of the Fallow deer?",options:["Red, Brown, Black, White","Common, Menil, Melanistic, White","Spotted, Striped, Melanistic, Albino","Common, Sandy, Dark, Pale"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Fallow deer have four main coat variations: Common (spotted summer, dark winter), Menil (paler, keeps spots all year), Melanistic (very dark/black), and White."},
  {category:"Identification",question:"On a classic, fully mature Red stag, what are the names of the first three tines growing from the coronet upwards?",options:["Trez, Bez, Brow","Brow, Trez, Crown","Brow, Bez, Trez","Coronet, Pearl, Fork"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Starting from the bottom (coronet), the tines on a Red stag are traditionally named the Brow, the Bez, and the Trez, culminating in the terminal points known as the Crown."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"At what time of year do you typically see a Roe buck with its antlers fully covered in velvet?",options:["Late Summer (August)","Mid-Winter to Early Spring (January to April)","Autumn (October)","They never grow velvet"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Because Roe bucks cast their antlers in early winter, they grow their new set during the winter and early spring, typically in velvet from January to April."},
  {category:"Identification",question:"Which deer species is most strongly associated with wetland habitats, such as reedbeds, fens, and marshy river valleys in the UK?",options:["Roe Deer","Fallow Deer","Chinese Water Deer","Sika"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"The Chinese Water Deer (CWD) strongly prefers wet, marshy habitats, which is why their UK population is heavily concentrated in the fens of East Anglia."},
  {category:"Identification",question:"Which of the following physical characteristics is a key identification feature of a Muntjac?",options:["A distinctly humped or rounded back and a posture where the rump sits higher than the shoulders","A bright white tail that flags when running","Large palmate antlers","A pale, sandy-coloured mane"],correctIndex:0,explanation:"Muntjac have a very distinct posture; they appear hunched with a rounded back, and their hind legs are longer than their front legs."},
  {category:"Identification",question:"When identifying Sika deer, what feature is often visible on their lower hind legs?",options:["A bright red stripe","A distinct, prominent tuft of light-coloured hair marking the metatarsal gland","Complete absence of hair","A black circular spot"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Sika deer have a very prominent, often lighter-coloured tuft of hair covering the metatarsal gland on the outside of their lower hind legs."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"What is the primary function of a deer's 'pedicle'?",options:["It is the bone in the lower leg that allows them to jump high","It is the permanent bony stalk on the frontal bone of the skull from which the antler grows","It is the gland that produces scent for marking","It is the upper section of the digestive tract"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"The pedicle is a permanent part of the male deer's skull. The temporary antler grows from the top of this pedicle each year."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"Why do deer selectively eat herbs, young shoots, and buds rather than just bulk grass?",options:["Because grass is poisonous to them","Because they are 'concentrate selectors' and require easily digestible, highly nutritious forage","Because their teeth cannot cut grass","Because grass makes them too thirsty"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Deer (especially Roe) are concentrate selectors. They have relatively small stomachs and must select high-nutrient, easily fermentable plant parts."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"Under the Highways Act 1980, it is an offence to discharge a firearm within 50 feet of the center of a public highway ONLY IF what condition is met?",options:["You are using a calibre larger than .243","It causes injury, interruption, or danger to a user of the highway","You do not have a silencer fitted","You shoot across the road"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Shooting within 50 feet of the center of a highway only becomes an offence if the action causes injury, interruption, or danger to road users."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"What legal documentation must you carry to prove you are permitted to stalk on a specific piece of land?",options:["Your Firearm Certificate alone, without written authority covering that specific land and sporting rights","Written permission (authorization) from the landowner or holder of the sporting rights","A police Firearms Enquiry Officer letter stating you may possess a rifle (without land-specific authority)","A national shooting or deer-stalking membership card, without permission tied to that ground"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Best practice and Police guidance strongly dictate that you must have written permission from the landowner or sporting rights holder."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"According to the Deer Act 1991, what is the strict legal definition of 'Night' regarding the prohibition of shooting deer?",options:["From 8:00 PM to 6:00 AM local time, year-round, regardless of daylight","From the moment of sunset at the site to the moment of sunrise at the site","From the expiration of the first hour after sunset to the beginning of the last hour before sunrise","When the stalker cannot reliably identify the target without artificial illumination"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"The legal definition of night in the Deer Act begins one hour after sunset and ends one hour before sunrise."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"Under the Hunting Act 2004, what is the legal restriction regarding the use of dogs when deer stalking?",options:["Dogs are completely banned from being present on a stalk","You may use a maximum of two dogs to flush a deer from cover to be shot by a waiting gun, but hunting and killing deer with a pack of hounds is illegal","You may use any number of dogs to chase and exhaust the deer","Dogs can only be used at night"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"While traditional hunting with hounds is illegal, you may legally use dogs to track a wounded deer, or use up to two dogs to flush a deer out of cover."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"Under what specific circumstance may an 'occupier' of enclosed land legally shoot a deer out of season?",options:["If the deer appears visibly unhealthy or unthrifty","If the deer is causing or is likely to cause serious damage to crops, vegetables, or growing timber on enclosed land","If the occupier wishes to harvest venison for personal consumption","If the animal is an antlered male rather than a female"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"The 'Farmer's Defence' allows out-of-season shooting only to prevent active, serious damage on enclosed land when non-lethal methods are impractical or have failed."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"What does the term 'Expanding Ammunition' refer to, which is legally required for shooting deer?",options:["Bullets that explode on contact with the skin","Bullets designed to deform and expand their diameter in a controlled manner upon entering soft tissue","Bullets that break into hundreds of pieces mid-air","Armor-piercing bullets"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Expanding ammunition (like soft-points or ballistic tips) peels back upon impact, transferring energy effectively into the vital organs."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"If you borrow an estate rifle under the 'Estate Rifle' exemption, what age must the borrower be?",options:["Over 14","17 or over","Over 18","Over 21"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Under Section 16 of the Firearms (Amendment) Act 1988, a person aged 17 or over may borrow a rifle from the occupier and use it on that land in their presence."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"In England and Wales, what is the closed season for Chinese Water Deer?",options:["1st March to 31st October","1st April to 31st October","1st November to 31st March","There is no statutory closed season for Chinese Water Deer"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Under the Deer Act 1991 Schedule 1, Chinese Water Deer (both bucks and does) have a closed season from 1st April to 31st October. Muntjac are the only UK species with no statutory closed season."},
  {category:"Ballistics",question:"What does the acronym MPBR stand for in rifle ballistics?",options:["Minimum Point Blank Range","Maximum Point Blank Range","Mean Penetration Bullet Radius","Muzzle Pressure Bullet Rating"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Maximum Point Blank Range is the distance over which the bullet's trajectory remains within a predetermined vital zone size without needing to adjust the point of aim."},
  {category:"Ballistics",question:"When evaluating a backstop, why is a flat body of water considered extremely dangerous?",options:["Because the bullet will sink instantly","Because bullets easily ricochet off the surface of water and can travel in unpredictable directions with lethal force","Because it makes a loud splash","Because water slows the bullet too quickly"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Water acts as a hard surface when hit at high velocities. A bullet striking water at a shallow angle will deflect and skip, endangering anything on the opposite shore."},
  {category:"Safety",question:"What is the consequence of getting oil or grease inside the chamber of your rifle before firing?",options:["It makes the bullet travel faster","It protects the brass cartridge","It prevents the brass case from gripping the chamber walls, which violently increases the rearward thrust against the bolt face, potentially causing a failure","It has no negative effect"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"The chamber must be completely dry. Oil prevents the expanding brass cartridge from sealing and gripping the steel walls, sending dangerous pressure backward onto the bolt face."},
  {category:"Safety",question:"What is the safest and most stable unsupported shooting position in the field?",options:["Standing","Kneeling","Sitting","Prone (lying down)"],correctIndex:3,explanation:"The prone position provides the maximum contact with the ground, lowering your center of gravity and minimizing body movement."},
  {category:"Fieldcraft",question:"When taking a broadside shot at a deer, where is the ideal point of aim to ensure a humane dispatch?",options:["High on the shoulder blade","In the center of the neck","Just behind the crease of the front shoulder, about one-third of the way up the body from the brisket","Directly behind the ear"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Aiming slightly behind the front leg and a third of the way up the chest ensures the bullet strikes the heart and major lung tissue."},

  // BATCH 5 — Identification Q121-Q130 + Legislation Q131-Q140 + Ballistics Q141-Q146 + Hygiene Q147-Q150
  {category:"Identification",question:"How many points (tines) does a fully mature, typical Roe buck have on its antlers?",options:["Four (two on each side)","Six (three on each side)","Eight (four on each side)","Ten (five on each side)"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"A typical mature Roe buck develops a total of six points: a forward-facing point, a top point, and a backward-facing point on each of the two antlers."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"What is a 'Pricket'?",options:["A female Fallow deer","A male Red deer with no antlers","A yearling Fallow buck in its second year, typically growing its first set of simple spike antlers","A tool used to gralloch a deer"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"In traditional deer terminology, a yearling Fallow buck growing its first set of unbranched spikes is called a Pricket."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"What is the primary biological function of the 'velvet' covering a developing antler?",options:["To provide camouflage during the summer","To keep the deer's head warm","To provide a highly vascular blood supply that delivers oxygen and nutrients to the rapidly growing bone","To absorb moisture from rain"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Velvet is a living, blood-rich skin tissue. Once the antler bone has fully calcified and grown, the blood supply is cut off, the velvet dies, and the deer rubs it off."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"Which of the UK deer species is physically the smallest?",options:["Chinese Water Deer","Roe Deer","Muntjac","Sika"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"The Muntjac is the smallest UK deer species, typically standing only 45-52 cm at the shoulder."},
  {category:"Identification",question:"When observing a Fallow deer, what is the most obvious visual difference between it and a Roe deer (aside from size)?",options:["Fallow deer have a much longer tail, often constantly twitching, and a distinct black horseshoe mark on the rump","Fallow deer have no visible tail","Fallow deer have prominent canine tusks","Roe deer have palmate antlers"],correctIndex:0,explanation:"Fallow deer possess a long, prominent tail (often with a black stripe) surrounded by a black horseshoe-shaped marking on their rump."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"How do deer primarily perceive and react to stationary objects?",options:["They have excellent binocular vision and can identify stationary shapes easily","They struggle to identify stationary objects and rely heavily on detecting movement, scent, or sound","They use echolocation","They can only see in complete darkness"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"A deer's vision is highly attuned to picking up the slightest movement. If a stalker remains perfectly still and the wind is in their favour, a deer will often look directly at them without recognizing them as a threat."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"What is the common term used for deer droppings?",options:["Scat","Fewmets (or pellets)","Spore","Slots"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Deer droppings are traditionally called fewmets, though they are most commonly referred to simply as pellets. A footprint is a 'slot'."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"Why is it biologically inaccurate to age a mature deer strictly by the size of its antlers or the number of points?",options:["Because antlers never stop growing year after year","Because deer only grow antlers once in their lifetime","Because antler development is heavily influenced by genetics, annual nutrition, and general health, not just age","Because all deer of the same species have identical antlers"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"An older deer in poor habitat may grow much smaller antlers than a younger deer in prime, nutrient-rich habitat. Tooth wear is the most practical field method for ageing deer."},
  {category:"Identification",question:"Which deer species has a highly distinct, V-shaped dark marking running down the forehead to the nose, particularly prominent in males?",options:["Roe","Sika","Muntjac","Chinese Water Deer"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Male Muntjac have a very prominent, dark V-shaped pattern on their face, which aligns with their large frontal scent glands."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"When do Red hinds typically give birth to their calves?",options:["January to February","March to April","Late May to June","September to October"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Following the October rut and an 8-month gestation period, Red hinds typically drop their calves in late May or June."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"If a stalker enters private land with a firearm without the permission of the landowner or the sporting rights holder, what specific legal offence are they committing?",options:["Poaching","Armed Trespass","Vagrancy","Disturbing the peace"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Entering land with a firearm without lawful authority or a reasonable excuse constitutes Armed Trespass, which is a very serious criminal offence under the Firearms Act."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"You shoot a deer on land where you have permission, but it runs across the boundary and collapses on a neighbouring property where you DO NOT have permission. What must you do?",options:["Leave your rifle behind, cross the boundary quickly, and drag it back","Shoot it again from your side of the boundary","You must stop, unload, and secure the landowner's permission before crossing the boundary","Send your dog over to fetch it"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"You have no legal right to cross a boundary to retrieve game. You must obtain the neighbour's permission; otherwise, crossing the boundary (especially with a firearm) constitutes armed trespass."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"Under the Deer Act 1991, which of the following weapons is strictly prohibited for shooting deer in the UK?",options:["A bolt-action rifle","A bow and arrow or crossbow","A single-shot rifle","A sound-moderated rifle"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"The Deer Act explicitly outlaws the use of bows, crossbows, spears, air rifles, and traps for the killing or taking of deer in the UK."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"In England and Wales, what is the open season for a Fallow Buck?",options:["1st April to 31st October","1st August to 30th April","1st November to 31st March","1st September to 20th October"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Fallow Bucks (like Red and Sika Stags) are in season in England and Wales from 1st August to 30th April."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"If you are driving and accidentally hit and severely injure a deer on the road, what is your legal position regarding dispatching it?",options:["You must wait for the police to arrive","Under the Deer Act exemptions, any person may use any reasonable means to humanely dispatch a deer to prevent further suffering","You must call a veterinarian to euthanize it","You are legally required to leave it alone"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"The law provides an exemption allowing anyone to dispatch a severely injured deer to end its suffering."},
  {category:"Safety",question:"If a public footpath crosses the land you are stalking on, what is your legal and safety obligation?",options:["You cannot shoot within a mile of the footpath","You must close the footpath while stalking","You must never fire a shot across the footpath or in a direction where a user of the path could be endangered","You have priority, and walkers must wear high-visibility clothing"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Public rights of way must be respected. You must ensure absolutely safe backstops and clear lines of sight so that no member of the public is ever endangered."},
  {category:"Ballistics",question:"When setting up to take a shot, why must you NEVER rest the actual barrel of the rifle directly on a hard surface?",options:["It will scratch the bluing on the barrel","Resting the barrel alters its natural harmonics and vibration during firing, causing the bullet to strike erratically and usually significantly higher","It makes the rifle too loud","It increases the recoil into your shoulder"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Rifle barrels whip and vibrate when fired. If the barrel touches a hard surface, these harmonics are violently interrupted, throwing the shot completely off target."},
  {category:"Fieldcraft",question:"You fire at a deer and observe bright red blood spraying rhythmically at the shot site. What does this indicate?",options:["A liver hit","A gut hit","A strike to a major artery (e.g., the heart or aorta)","A non-lethal muscle hit"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Bright red, pulsing or spraying blood is a classic indicator of massive arterial damage, usually resulting from a well-placed heart or major vessel shot."},
  {category:"Fieldcraft",question:"What is the primary visual difference between a deer hit in the heart/lungs versus a deer hit in the stomach?",options:["A gut-shot deer drops instantly; a heart-shot deer runs for miles","A heart-shot deer may leap or kick out its hind legs and sprint; a gut-shot deer typically arches its back, humps up, and walks slowly into cover","There is no visual difference in their reaction","A gut-shot deer will always vocalize loudly"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"The 'humped back' and slow walk is the universal sign of a gut shot. A heart shot usually results in a dramatic leap or 'death run'."},
  {category:"Fieldcraft",question:"When extracting a culled deer from the field, what is the best practice to maintain carcass hygiene?",options:["Drag it through a muddy stream to wash it","Drag the deer by its hind legs so the chest cavity acts as a scoop for mud and debris","Seal the chest/abdominal cavity if opened, or suspend the deer on a drag tray/sled, to prevent mud from contaminating the exposed meat","Throw it over your shoulder immediately"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Dragging an open carcass across the ground forces mud and bacteria directly into the sterile meat cavity."},
  {category:"Safety",question:"What is the danger of carrying a rifle with a round in the chamber and the safety catch on while navigating through thick woodland?",options:["The safety catch is a mechanical device that can be accidentally brushed off by a twig or fail entirely, leading to a negligent discharge","The bullet might fall out of the chamber","The rifle will become too heavy to carry safely","It is perfectly safe as long as the safety is on"],correctIndex:0,explanation:"Never trust a safety catch in dense cover or when crossing obstacles. The rifle should be unloaded (chamber empty) until you are in a clear position to shoot."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"Which of the following organs is NOT part of the 'pluck' (the internal organs inspected by the Trained Person)?",options:["Heart","Lungs","Liver","Rumen (Stomach)"],correctIndex:3,explanation:"The pluck consists of the trachea, lungs, heart, diaphragm, and liver. The stomach and intestines are part of the digestive tract and are carefully removed in the field."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"What is the correct hygiene protocol if you drop your gralloching knife on the ground?",options:["Wipe it on the deer's hide and continue","Wipe it on the grass","Clean it thoroughly with potable water and sterilize it (e.g., using alcohol wipes or water at 82°C) before it touches the meat again","Ignore it, soil bacteria are harmless"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Soil harbors extremely dangerous bacteria. A dropped knife is contaminated and must be sterilized to prevent transferring that bacteria deep into the carcass meat."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"What is the purpose of placing a fly net or mesh bag over a hanging carcass in the larder?",options:["To keep the carcass warm","To prevent blowflies from landing on the meat and laying eggs, which rapidly hatch into destructive maggots","To absorb dripping blood","To hide the carcass from view"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Blowflies are attracted to the scent of the carcass instantly. A fly net allows airflow for cooling while creating a physical barrier to prevent 'fly strike'."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"If you observe a live deer staggering in circles, appearing blind, and entirely unafraid of humans, what should you suspect and how should you proceed?",options:["It is simply old; shoot it and sell it normally","It is suffering from a severe neurological issue or disease. It must be culled on welfare grounds, but the carcass should NOT enter the food chain","It is drunk on fermented apples; leave it alone","Capture it and take it to a vet"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Severe neurological symptoms indicate serious disease or brain injury. It must be dispatched to end suffering, but is unfit for human consumption."},

  // Additional questions from batches 6-10 to reach 300
  {category:"Safety",question:"When dragging a culled deer from the field with a companion, what is the most important firearm safety rule?",options:["Ensure the rifle is unloaded and slung securely so the muzzle never points at your companion","Leave the rifle hidden in the woods","Keep the rifle loaded in case you see another deer","Hand the rifle to the person doing the dragging"],correctIndex:0,explanation:"Muzzle awareness and safe handling do not stop once the deer is dead. The rifle must be proven clear and carried safely during the physical exertion of the extraction."},
  {category:"Safety",question:"When approaching a downed deer, what is the safest method to confirm it is dead before commencing the gralloch?",options:["Kick it in the ribs","Approach from behind, keep the rifle ready, and gently touch the open eye with a stick to check for a blink reflex","Shout loudly at it","Slit its throat immediately"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Always approach cautiously from the dorsal (spine) side, never the hooves. Touching the eye checks the corneal reflex; if it doesn't blink, the animal is dead."},
  {category:"Safety",question:"Before climbing into a high seat, what is the first check you must perform?",options:["Check the wind direction","Visually and physically inspect the structure, rungs, and straps for rot, rust, or damage to ensure it can bear your weight","Check the rifle is loaded","Check for ticks"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"High seats degrade over time. A catastrophic structural failure while climbing or sitting is a major safety hazard."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"What is the primary food hygiene reason for extracting the stomach and intestines from the carcass as soon as possible after shooting?",options:["To make the carcass lighter to carry","To feed local scavengers","To remove the primary source of heat and internal bacteria, allowing the carcass to cool rapidly and preventing meat spoilage","To inspect the stomach contents"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"The digestive tract acts like a hot water bottle inside the deer and is full of bacteria. Removing it quickly (gralloching) is the single most important step in preserving venison quality."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"Which of the following describes the correct appearance of the submaxillary and retropharyngeal lymph nodes in a healthy deer?",options:["Large, red, and soft","Small, firm, and grey/brown","Swollen and filled with yellow gritty pus","White and calcified"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Healthy lymph nodes are relatively inconspicuous, firm, and greyish-brown. Swelling, pus, or calcification are signs of active or past infection."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"What does the acronym AGHE stand for?",options:["Approved Game Handling Establishment","Association of Game Hunters England","Agricultural Game and Habitat Executive","Authorized Game Haulage Enterprise"],correctIndex:0,explanation:"An AGHE is a commercial facility licensed to receive, process, and sell wild game meat to the general public and retail sectors."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"Following the legislative changes in late 2023, what is the statutory closed season for all MALE deer species in Scotland?",options:["1st May to 31st July","21st October to 31st March","There is no longer a closed season for any male deer species in Scotland","1st April to 31st October"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"In October 2023, the Scottish Government abolished the closed season for all male deer in Scotland. England and Wales still have closed seasons for male deer."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"In England and Wales, what is the statutory open season for female Red, Fallow, and Sika deer?",options:["1st August to 30th April","1st November to 31st March","1st April to 31st October","There is no closed season"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Female large deer are in season during the winter months, from November 1st to March 31st, to protect them while heavily pregnant or rearing dependent young."},
  {category:"Identification",question:"Which deer species is identifiable by a distinctly short, white tail with a distinct, thin black stripe running down the center of it?",options:["Fallow","Sika","Muntjac","Roe"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Sika deer are identifiable by this specific tail pattern, which sits against a bright white, heart-shaped rump patch bordered by black."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"What is the proper term for a female Roe deer?",options:["Hind","Doe","Cow","Heifer"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Female Roe, Fallow, Muntjac, and CWD are called Does. Female Red and Sika are called Hinds."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"What is the proper term for a male Red deer?",options:["Buck","Bull","Stag","Pricket"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Male Red and Sika deer are called Stags. Male Roe, Fallow, Muntjac, and CWD are called Bucks."},
  {category:"Identification",question:"Which of the following describes the distinctive rutting call of a Sika stag?",options:["A deep, guttural roar","A sharp, repetitive bark","A high-pitched, eerie, triple whistle or scream","A rhythmic, belching groan"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"The Sika stag produces a very distinctive, rising and falling triple whistle or shriek, completely different from the roar of a Red stag."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"What is the average gestation period of a Roe doe?",options:["5 months","10 months (including delayed implantation)","7 months","12 months"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Roe deer mate in July/August, but the embryo does not implant until late December/January (delayed implantation). The kids are born in May/June, making the total gestation around 10 months."},
  {category:"Identification",question:"Which deer species has males that grow prominent, long upper canine teeth (tusks) but never grow antlers?",options:["Muntjac","Sika","Roe","Chinese Water Deer"],correctIndex:3,explanation:"Chinese Water Deer completely lack antlers. Males rely on their long, sharp canine tusks for defence and fighting."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"What is a 'cast' antler?",options:["An antler that has been broken in a fight","An antler that has naturally dropped off the pedicle at the end of the annual cycle","An antler still covered in velvet","An artificially shaped antler"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Casting is the natural, annual process where the old antler detaches from the pedicle to make way for the growth of a new set."},
  {category:"Identification",question:"During the rut, what is the characteristic vocalization made by a Fallow buck?",options:["A high-pitched whistle","A deep, rhythmic groaning or belching sound","A sharp bark","A loud, clear roar"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Fallow bucks produce a deep, repetitive, belching groan during the rut to attract does and warn off rival males."},
  {category:"Identification",question:"Which of the following UK deer species is most likely to be found grazing in large, mixed-sex herds in open parkland?",options:["Chinese Water Deer","Roe Deer","Fallow Deer","Muntjac"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Fallow deer are highly gregarious and frequently form large herds. The other species listed tend to be much more solitary."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"What is the primary natural trigger that causes a male deer to shed the velvet from his antlers?",options:["A drop in temperature","A decrease in food availability","A surge in testosterone levels as the rut approaches","The antlers becoming too heavy"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Rising testosterone levels cause the antler bone to fully harden and the blood supply to the velvet to stop. The dead velvet is then frayed off against vegetation."},
  {category:"Identification",question:"Which non-native deer species is easily identified by its small size, hunched posture, and a wide, dark V-shape marking on the male's forehead?",options:["Chinese Water Deer","Muntjac","Sika","Roe"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"The Muntjac has a distinct hunched posture and prominent facial markings that align with their large frontal scent glands."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"Under the Deer Act, what is the strict legal restriction on shooting deer from a vehicle?",options:["You can shoot from a vehicle if it is moving under 10 mph","It is completely illegal under all circumstances","The vehicle must be entirely stationary and the engine must be switched off","You can only shoot from a vehicle if you have a disabled shooter's permit"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Shooting from a moving or running vehicle is a serious safety hazard and is strictly prohibited by law. You may use a stationary vehicle with the engine off."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"What is the primary food hygiene reason for 'bleeding' the carcass immediately after dispatch?",options:["To reduce weight","To prevent blood from pooling in the muscle tissue, which encourages rapid bacterial growth and spoils the meat","To make skinning easier","To attract scavengers"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Draining the blood quickly cools the carcass and removes a prime breeding ground for bacteria, vastly improving the venison's shelf life."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"How does 'cross-contamination' typically occur during the field gralloch?",options:["By hanging two deer next to each other","By using a knife that has touched the dirty hide, soil, or feces to subsequently cut into the clean, sterile muscle tissue","By using a dirty rifle","By washing the deer in a stream"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"The muscle meat is sterile. Bacteria live on the skin and in the gut. Using the same unsterilized knife for both transfers the bacteria directly onto the food product."},
  {category:"Fieldcraft",question:"When you need to cross a barbed-wire fence while stalking alone, what is the safest procedure?",options:["Sling the loaded rifle across your back","Keep the safety catch on and climb carefully","Unload the rifle, open the bolt, safely pass it through or place it on the ground on the far side, cross over, and retrieve it","Hand the loaded rifle over the fence first"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Never navigate obstacles with a loaded firearm. You must make the weapon completely safe before crossing."},
  {category:"Fieldcraft",question:"Why is it essential to stalk into or across the wind?",options:["To prevent bullet drift","Because a deer's primary defense is its acute sense of smell; stalking with the wind at your back will push your scent directly to them","To keep noise levels down","Because deer only look downwind"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Scent is the most reliable warning system a deer has. You must always ensure your scent is blown away from the area you are stalking into."},
  {category:"Fieldcraft",question:"You shoot a deer and it immediately arches its back, humps up, and slowly walks into thick cover. What does this reaction indicate?",options:["A perfect heart shot","A clean miss","A painful gut shot","A high neck shot"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"The hunched posture is the universal sign of a gut shot. The animal is in pain and must be given 45-60 minutes to bed down before tracking."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"How do deer physically digest tough plant material like leaves and bark?",options:["By chewing it once with sharp upper incisors","By swallowing it whole and letting stomach acid dissolve it","By fermenting it in the rumen and later regurgitating it to chew again (ruminating)","By eating soil to grind the food in their stomach"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Deer are ruminants. They swallow food quickly, store it in the rumen, and later find a safe place to regurgitate and 'chew the cud' to break down the tough cellulose."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"When storing a firearm and ammunition at home, what is the fundamental legal requirement?",options:["They must be kept in the same safe for quick access","The ammunition must be stored securely in a separate, lockable compartment away from the firearm","Ammunition can be left on a shelf as long as the rifle is locked","The rifle must have the bolt left in it"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"To prevent unauthorized access and theft, the law requires that ammunition and firearms be stored securely and separately."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"Which of the following is a Notifiable Disease characterized by blisters and painful ulcers on the mouth, tongue, and hooves?",options:["Bovine Tuberculosis","Foot and Mouth Disease","Anthrax","Lyme Disease"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"These are the classic symptoms of Foot and Mouth Disease, which is highly contagious to livestock and must be reported immediately."},
  {category:"Safety",question:"Why should a stalker wear hearing protection even when using a sound-moderated rifle?",options:["To stay warm","Because the moderator only suppresses the muzzle blast; the supersonic 'crack' of the bullet is still loud enough to cause permanent hearing damage over time","Because it is a legal requirement","To improve concentration"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"High-velocity hunting bullets break the sound barrier, producing a loud sonic boom that cannot be silenced by a moderator."},
  {category:"Ballistics",question:"What makes soft earth or a rising grassy bank the ideal backstop?",options:["It makes the bullet ricochet upwards safely","It reliably absorbs the bullet's remaining kinetic energy and traps it without deflecting it","It is easier to find the bullet later","It provides better camouflage for the stalker"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"A safe backstop must reliably trap the bullet. Hard surfaces cause ricochets, and vegetation does not stop a bullet. Soft, deep earth absorbs the impact safely."},
  {category:"Identification",question:"In winter, how can you visually identify a female Roe deer (doe) from behind?",options:["She has a completely black rump","She has a prominent downward tuft of hair called a 'tush' covering her vulva, making her white rump patch look like an inverted heart","Her rump patch is oval-shaped with no tufts","She has a long, twitching tail"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"The 'tush' is a distinct winter feature of the Roe doe. It alters the shape of the flared white rump patch, helping stalkers differentiate sexes when antlers are cast."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"What is the legally required maximum core temperature for a large wild game carcass before it is transported to an AGHE?",options:["0°C","4°C","7°C","10°C"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Hygiene regulations stipulate a maximum core temperature of 7°C to inhibit bacterial growth during transport."},
  {category:"Fieldcraft",question:"At the shot site, you find bright pink, frothy blood. What does this tell you?",options:["The bullet struck the liver","The bullet struck the lungs, mixing highly oxygenated blood with air","The bullet grazed a leg","The bullet struck the stomach"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Pink, frothy blood is the definitive indicator of a lethal chest/lung shot. Wait 10-15 minutes before following up."},
  {category:"Identification",question:"Which deer species communicates alarm with a repetitive, sharp, fox-like bark?",options:["Red Deer","Roe Deer","Muntjac","Sika"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Muntjac are frequently referred to as 'barking deer' due to their loud, repetitive alarm call when they sense danger."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"Is it lawful to use a shotgun to shoot deer for sport in the UK?",options:["Yes, if using birdshot","Yes, in dense woodland","No, it is generally illegal; shotguns may only be used under very specific exemptions","Yes, but only for Muntjac"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"The Deer Act generally prohibits shotguns for taking deer, providing narrow exemptions only for preventing severe suffering or serious agricultural damage."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"At birth, what distinctive coat feature do Red deer calves and Fallow fawns share to help them camouflage?",options:["A black dorsal stripe","A bright white tail","A heavily white-spotted coat that breaks up their outline in dappled sunlight","A thick grey mane"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Both Red calves and Fallow fawns are born with spotted coats for camouflage. Red deer lose these spots as they mature."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"When do Roe bucks typically cast their antlers?",options:["March and April","May and June","November and December","July and August"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Roe bucks cast their antlers in early winter (Nov/Dec) and regrow them over the winter/spring, stripping the velvet around April."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"Which of the following describes the correct appearance of healthy lungs during the gralloch?",options:["Dark purple, heavy, and solid","Bright pink, light, spongy, and free from hard lumps","Covered in yellow pus","White and calcified"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Healthy lungs are bright pink and spongy. Hard lumps or caseous lesions could indicate Tuberculosis."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"How many points (tines) does a typical, fully mature Roe buck have?",options:["Four","Six","Eight","Ten"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"A typical mature Roe buck grows a total of six points: three on each antler (a forward point, a top point, and a rear point)."},
  {category:"Identification",question:"Which UK deer species leaves a very small slot (footprint) where one cleave is often noticeably longer than the other?",options:["Roe","Chinese Water Deer","Muntjac","Sika"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Muntjac slots are tiny (about 2.5cm) and frequently display unequal cleaves, helping to distinguish their tracks from small Roe deer."},
  {category:"Fieldcraft",question:"What is the safest way to approach a downed deer to confirm it is dead?",options:["Walk up to its head and poke it","Approach cautiously from the dorsal (spine) side, keep the rifle ready, and touch the open eye with a stick to check for a blink reflex","Shout at it from a distance","Grab its hind legs"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Approaching from the spine keeps you safe from kicking hooves. Checking the corneal reflex (eye blink) confirms if the central nervous system is dead."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"What is the primary role of a 'Trained Person' regarding wild game meat?",options:["To butcher the meat for supermarkets","To conduct a primary field inspection of the carcass and viscera to ensure there are no signs of disease or contamination before it enters the food chain","To certify the rifle used was legal","To transport the meat"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"The Trained Person signs a declaration confirming they have inspected the organs and carcass and found no abnormalities, allowing the AGHE to accept the meat."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"Who is legally responsible for ensuring that a specific shot taken on a piece of land is safe?",options:["The landowner","The police who cleared the land","The person squeezing the trigger","The British Deer Society"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"The ultimate legal and moral responsibility for the safety of a shot always rests entirely with the shooter."},
  {category:"Safety",question:"If your rifle suffers a misfire or hang-fire (a click but no bang), what must you do?",options:["Immediately open the bolt to eject the faulty round","Keep the rifle pointed at the safe backstop and wait at least 30 seconds in case the primer detonates late","Look down the barrel to check for obstructions","Pull the trigger again"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"A hang-fire is a delayed ignition. Opening the bolt immediately exposes your face to a potential explosion if the cartridge detonates late."},
  {category:"Ballistics",question:"Why does the Deer Act require the use of 'expanding' ammunition?",options:["To ensure the bullet never exits the animal","Because it expands on impact, transferring maximum energy into the vital organs for a rapid, humane death","Because it travels faster than solid bullets","Because it ruins less meat"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Expanding bullets (soft points) create a massive wound channel and hydrostatic shock, ensuring the animal drops quickly."},
  {category:"Identification",question:"Which species of deer is identifiable by a distinctly hunched posture, where the rump appears higher than the shoulders?",options:["Chinese Water Deer","Roe Deer","Fallow Deer","Muntjac"],correctIndex:3,explanation:"Muntjac have longer hind legs than front legs, giving them a characteristic hunched, 'head-down' appearance when standing or walking."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"What is the biological term for the shedding of the velvet from the hardened antler?",options:["Casting","Fraying","Browsing","Thrashing"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Fraying is the process where the deer vigorously rubs its antlers against small trees and shrubs to strip away the dead velvet."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"Which of the following is a Notifiable Disease that must be reported immediately to the APHA or Police?",options:["Foot and Mouth Disease","Lyme Disease","Lungworm","Liver Fluke"],correctIndex:0,explanation:"Foot and Mouth Disease is highly contagious to livestock and is strictly Notifiable. Symptoms include blisters and ulcers on the mouth, tongue, and hooves."},
  {category:"Safety",question:"What surface condition presents the highest risk of a dangerous bullet ricochet?",options:["Soft, ploughed soil","Deep sand","Hard, frozen, or rocky ground","A grassy bank"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Hard surfaces prevent the bullet from penetrating and expanding. Instead, the bullet glances off and deflects in unpredictable directions."},
  {category:"Fieldcraft",question:"When planning a stalk, how should you use the wind?",options:["Stalk with the wind blowing from your back to the deer","Ignore the wind and focus on remaining quiet","Stalk into the wind (wind blowing from the deer to you) or across the wind, to prevent your scent reaching the animal","Stalk only when there is no wind"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"A deer will smell a human long before it sees or hears them. You must always keep your scent blowing away from your target area."},
  {category:"Identification",question:"Which UK deer species is most commonly found in the wet reedbeds, fens, and marshlands of East Anglia?",options:["Chinese Water Deer","Fallow","Red","Sika"],correctIndex:0,explanation:"Chinese Water Deer (CWD) strongly prefer wet, boggy habitats, making the East Anglian fens their ideal UK stronghold."},
// Extra questions to reach 300 total

// More Biology
  {category:"Biology",question:"What is the collective term for a group of female Red deer?",options:["A flock","A bevy","A herd","A parcel"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"A group of Red deer is called a herd. Roe deer form a bevy, and Fallow a parcel or herd."},
  {category:"Identification",question:"When observing a Roe deer's rump patch, how can you visually distinguish a female (doe) from a male (buck) in the winter?",options:["The doe has no rump patch","The doe's rump patch is shaped like an inverted heart with a downward tuft of hair (tush), while the buck's is kidney or oval-shaped","The buck's rump patch is black","The doe has a long black tail covering the patch"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"In winter, the female Roe deer has a prominent downward tuft of hair called a 'tush' covering her vulva, making the white rump patch look like an inverted heart."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"What is the technical term for the thick, hollow, insulating hair found in a deer's winter coat?",options:["Fleece","Kemp","Down","Velvet"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Kemp hairs are thick, brittle, and hollow. They trap air brilliantly, providing the deer with exceptional thermal insulation during harsh winter weather."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"Which of the following native UK deer species is currently under threat of genetic dilution due to hybridization with Sika?",options:["Roe deer","Red deer","Fallow deer","Chinese Water Deer"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Because Sika and Red deer are closely related, they interbreed where their ranges overlap, creating fertile hybrids and threatening pure native Red deer bloodlines."},
  {category:"Identification",question:"If you observe a Fallow deer with a 'Melanistic' coat, what does it look like?",options:["Pure white","Sandy with prominent white spots","Almost entirely black or very dark brown, with no visible spots","Rusty red with a black dorsal stripe"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Melanistic Fallow deer have an overproduction of dark pigment, resulting in a coat that appears dark brown or black all year round."},
  {category:"Identification",question:"Which deer species has a relatively short, white tail with a distinct, thin black stripe running down the center?",options:["Fallow","Sika","Muntjac","Roe"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Sika deer are identifiable by this specific tail pattern, which sits against a bright white, heart-shaped rump patch bordered by black."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"How is the 'slot' (footprint) of a Muntjac distinguishable from that of a Roe deer?",options:["Muntjac slots are perfectly round","Muntjac slots are significantly smaller and often show one cleave slightly longer than the other","Muntjac slots are much wider and show dewclaws constantly","There is no visible difference"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Muntjac leave very small slots (around 2.5cm to 3cm long), and one cleave (half of the hoof) is often distinctly longer than the other."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"Why do deer selectively browse herbs and young shoots rather than simply grazing bulk grass?",options:["Because grass is poisonous to them","Because they are concentrate selectors requiring easily digestible, highly nutritious forage","Because their teeth cannot cut grass","Because grass makes them too thirsty"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Deer (especially Roe) are concentrate selectors. They have relatively small stomachs and must select high-nutrient, easily fermentable plant parts rather than bulky grasses."},
  {category:"Identification",question:"During the rut, which species produces a deep, rhythmic belching groan?",options:["Red stag","Sika stag","Fallow buck","Roe buck"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Fallow bucks produce a deep, repetitive, belching groan during the rut to attract does and warn off rival males. Red stags roar, and Sika stags whistle."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"Which UK deer species is most likely to be found grazing in large mixed-sex herds in open parkland?",options:["Chinese Water Deer","Roe Deer","Fallow Deer","Muntjac"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Fallow deer are highly gregarious and frequently form large herds. Roe tend to be solitary or in small family groups."},

// More Legislation
  {category:"Legislation",question:"Under Scottish law, what is the minimum legal muzzle velocity required to shoot Roe deer?",options:["2,000 feet per second","2,450 feet per second","3,000 feet per second","1,750 feet per second"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Scottish law specifies that ammunition used for Roe deer must achieve a minimum muzzle velocity of 2,450 fps (along with 50gr weight and 1,000 ft/lbs energy)."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"In England and Wales, what is the minimum muzzle energy required to shoot Muntjac and Chinese Water Deer?",options:["500 ft/lbs","1,000 ft/lbs","1,700 ft/lbs","1,750 ft/lbs"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"For the smallest deer species in England and Wales, the minimum legal muzzle energy is 1,000 foot-pounds (using a min .220 calibre and 50gr bullet)."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"In England and Wales, what is the open season for Fallow Does?",options:["1st August to 30th April","1st April to 31st October","1st November to 31st March","There is no closed season"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Female large deer (Red Hinds, Fallow Does, Sika Hinds) are in season during the winter months, from November 1st to March 31st."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"In Scotland, is it legal to shoot deer at night?",options:["Yes, if you use a thermal scope","Yes, on your own land","No, unless operating under a specific night-shooting authorisation from NatureScot","No, it is completely banned with no exceptions"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Night shooting is heavily restricted across the UK. In Scotland, it requires strict authorization from NatureScot, usually granted only to prevent severe agricultural damage."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"Under the 'Primary Producer' food hygiene exemptions, what are you legally allowed to do with small quantities of wild game you have culled?",options:["Sell it in-skin directly to the final consumer or to local retail establishments without needing an AGHE inspection","Sell it fully butchered to a national supermarket chain","Export it internationally without paperwork","Sell it to restaurants out of season"],correctIndex:0,explanation:"Primary producers can supply small quantities of primary products (in-skin carcasses) directly to the final consumer or local retailers supplying the final consumer, without passing through an AGHE."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"In England and Wales, what is the minimum calibre and muzzle energy required to shoot Roe deer?",options:[".240 calibre, 1700 ft/lbs",".220 calibre, 1000 ft/lbs",".270 calibre, 2000 ft/lbs",".22 LR, 150 ft/lbs"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"For the smaller species (Roe, Muntjac, CWD) in England and Wales, the minimum is a .220 calibre firing a bullet of at least 50 grains that produces 1000 ft/lbs of energy."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"In Scotland, what are the minimum legal requirements to shoot Roe deer?",options:["Bullet weight 50 grains, muzzle velocity 2,450 fps, muzzle energy 1,000 ft/lbs","Calibre .240, muzzle energy 1,700 ft/lbs","Bullet weight 100 grains, muzzle velocity 2,450 fps","There are no minimums"],correctIndex:0,explanation:"Scottish law specifies these three exact metrics for Roe deer: min 50gr weight, min 2,450 fps velocity, and min 1,000 ft/lbs energy."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"Under the Highways Act, when does discharging a firearm within 50 feet of the center of a highway become a criminal offence?",options:["Always, without exception","If it causes injury, interruption, or danger to a user of the highway","If you are shooting a calibre larger than .22","If you do not have a sound moderator fitted"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"It is only an offence if the discharge actively endangers, injures, or interrupts someone using the highway."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"What type of expanding ammunition is legally mandated for shooting deer in the UK?",options:["Full Metal Jacket (FMJ)","Armour piercing","Soft-nose or ballistic-tip bullets designed to deform predictably on impact","Solid brass bullets"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Expanding ammunition transfers kinetic energy rapidly into the vital organs, ensuring a quick and humane dispatch."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"Is it legal to use a vehicle to chase or drive deer towards waiting shooters?",options:["Yes, on private land","Yes, if driving under 15 mph","No, it is strictly illegal to use any mechanically propelled vehicle to drive deer","Yes, but only for Muntjac"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"The Deer Act explicitly outlaws the use of any mechanically propelled vehicle for the purpose of driving deer."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"What is the primary condition under which the 'Farmer's Defence' allows a deer to be shot out of season on enclosed land?",options:["If the deer is male","If the deer is causing serious damage to crops or growing timber, and non-lethal methods are ineffective","If the farmer wishes to sell the meat","If the deer is near a road"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"The exemption is strictly for crop and timber protection on enclosed land, and only when serious damage is actively occurring."},

// More Safety
  {category:"Safety",question:"What is the single most critical factor to confirm before squeezing the trigger on a deer?",options:["That the deer is standing still","That you have a safe, solid backstop immediately behind the target to safely trap the bullet","That your rifle is clean","That the sun is behind you"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Hunting bullets frequently pass through the animal. Without a safe backstop, the exiting bullet can travel for miles with lethal force."},
  {category:"Safety",question:"Why should you never rest the actual barrel of your rifle against a hard surface when taking a shot?",options:["It will scratch the barrel","It disrupts the natural harmonics and vibration of the barrel during firing, causing the bullet to strike erratically and usually high","It makes the rifle recoil harder","It suppresses the sound moderator"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Rifle barrels whip and vibrate minutely when a bullet travels down them. Contact with a hard surface interrupts this harmonic wave, throwing the shot off target. Always rest the stock, not the barrel."},
  {category:"Safety",question:"If you push the muzzle of your rifle into soft soil or snow, why must you visually inspect the bore before firing?",options:["Because a dirty barrel is less accurate","Because the dirt will scratch the rifling","Because even a minor blockage can cause a catastrophic pressure spike, resulting in the barrel bulging or exploding","Because it will make the gun too loud"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Firing a blocked barrel is incredibly dangerous. The super-heated expanding gases have nowhere to go, causing the steel barrel to rupture."},
  {category:"Safety",question:"Why is hearing protection strongly recommended when stalking with a centrefire rifle, even if a sound moderator is fitted?",options:["To improve concentration","Because the supersonic 'crack' of the bullet cannot be silenced and still produces noise levels capable of causing permanent, cumulative hearing damage","To keep your ears warm","Because the law strictly requires it"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Moderators reduce muzzle blast, but a centrefire bullet breaking the sound barrier still produces 130+ decibels of noise, which permanently damages hearing over time."},
  {category:"Safety",question:"What constitutes a 'safe backstop' when taking a shot at a deer?",options:["A clear view of the skyline","A thick hedge","Soft earth or a rising bank immediately behind the target that will securely trap the bullet","A flat lake"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"A safe backstop must reliably absorb the bullet's energy. Hedges offer no resistance, and water or skylines are extremely dangerous."},

// More Fieldcraft
  {category:"Fieldcraft",question:"You find bright red blood spraying rhythmically at the shot site. What does this indicate?",options:["A liver hit","A gut hit","A strike to a major artery (e.g., the heart or aorta)","A non-lethal muscle hit"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Bright red, pulsing or spraying blood is a classic indicator of massive arterial damage, usually resulting from a well-placed heart or major vessel shot."},
  {category:"Fieldcraft",question:"You take a shot and the deer drops instantly. Its head remains up and it tries to pull itself forward with its front legs. What has happened?",options:["It is a perfect heart shot","The bullet has struck the spine; the animal is paralyzed in the rear but fully conscious and suffering","The deer simply tripped","The bullet missed but the noise stunned it"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"An instant drop with the head remaining up usually indicates a spinal hit that missed the brain. The animal requires immediate dispatch."},
  {category:"Fieldcraft",question:"At the shot site, you find stomach contents, green fluid, and a foul smell. What is the correct action?",options:["Run after it immediately","Wait approximately 45 minutes to an hour before following up","Wait until the next morning","Abandon the stalk"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"A gut-shot deer will die, but if pushed immediately it will run for miles. Waiting allows it to bed down, stiffen, and make humane dispatch possible."},
  {category:"Fieldcraft",question:"While tracking, you find shattered white bone and clear, jelly-like fluid. What does this indicate?",options:["A heart shot","A liver shot","A non-lethal strike to a leg joint","A spine shot"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Bone fragments with synovial (joint) fluid indicate a leg shot. The deer is highly mobile but severely injured, and must be followed up immediately."},
  {category:"Fieldcraft",question:"You fire at a deer; it immediately arches its back, humps up, and walks away slowly. What does this reaction indicate?",options:["A heart shot","A clean miss","A gut shot (stomach or intestines)","A spine hit"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"The hunched posture and slow walk is the classic indicator of a painful stomach wound. The animal must be given time to bed down before tracking."},
  {category:"Fieldcraft",question:"At the shot site you find long, bright white hair. What does this indicate about shot placement?",options:["It was a perfect chest shot","The shot was too high","The shot was very low, likely grazing the brisket or the belly","It was a neck shot"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Long, bright white hair on most UK deer species originates from the belly or lower brisket area, indicating the shot was placed too low."},

// More Meat Hygiene
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"If a deer's rumen is punctured by the bullet and green stomach contents contaminate the inner flanks, what is the required hygiene response?",options:["Wash the cavity out thoroughly with water","Wipe it clean with a rag","Use a clean knife to trim away and safely discard all the contaminated meat","Leave it, as the dealer will clean it"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Washing or wiping spreads the bacteria over a larger surface area. You must physically cut away the contaminated tissue to ensure the rest of the carcass remains hygienic."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"When transporting a gralloched carcass in your vehicle, what is a key best-practice consideration?",options:["The deer should be tied to the bonnet","The carcass should be covered or transported out of sight in a tray to avoid causing alarm or distress to the public","The windows must be down to cool it","It must be transported in a refrigerated van within 1 hour"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Visible carcasses and blood can cause significant public distress and damage the reputation of deer management. Always transport deer discreetly."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"What is the primary vector for transmitting Lyme Disease to a deer stalker?",options:["Inhaling bacteria during the gralloch","Drinking contaminated stream water","The bite of an infected sheep tick (Ixodes ricinus)","Eating undercooked venison"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Lyme disease is carried by ticks. Stalkers moving through bracken and heather are at high risk and should check themselves thoroughly after every outing."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"If a Trained Person inspects a carcass and finds it healthy, who can they legally sell the in-skin carcass to?",options:["Any restaurant or hotel","A local butcher shop","An Approved Game Handling Establishment (AGHE) or licensed Venison Dealer","A supermarket"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Only an AGHE or licensed dealer can take an in-skin carcass and process it for the wider retail market. A Trained Person's declaration allows the AGHE to accept it."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"You find a deer that has died suddenly with dark, tar-like blood not clotting, oozing from its nose and anus. Which Notifiable Disease should you suspect?",options:["Anthrax","Tuberculosis","Chronic Wasting Disease","E. coli"],correctIndex:0,explanation:"Sudden death accompanied by dark, uncoagulated blood leaking from the body's orifices is the primary indicator of Anthrax, which is highly dangerous to humans."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"Where would you typically find Warble Fly larvae on a deer carcass?",options:["In the liver","In the nasal passages","Buried in small cysts just beneath the skin along the deer's back","In the lungs"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Warble fly larvae migrate through the body and form lumps under the skin on the back, where they breathe through a small hole, damaging the hide and local meat."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"When inspecting the liver, you notice flat, leaf-shaped parasites in the bile ducts. What are these?",options:["Liver flukes","Lungworms","Tapeworms","Nasal bots"],correctIndex:0,explanation:"Liver flukes infect the liver's bile ducts. While the affected parts of the liver must be discarded, the meat of the carcass is generally still safe for consumption."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"What is the correct hygiene protocol if you drop your gralloching knife on the ground?",options:["Wipe it on the deer's hide and continue","Wipe it on the grass","Clean it thoroughly and sterilize it before it touches the meat again","Ignore it, soil bacteria are harmless"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Soil harbors extremely dangerous bacteria. A dropped knife must be sterilized to prevent transferring bacteria deep into the carcass meat."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"What is the purpose of placing a fly net over a hanging carcass in the larder?",options:["To keep the carcass warm","To prevent blowflies from laying eggs which rapidly hatch into destructive maggots","To absorb dripping blood","To hide the carcass from view"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Blowflies are attracted to the scent of the carcass instantly. A fly net allows airflow for cooling while creating a physical barrier to prevent fly strike."},

// More Ballistics
  {category:"Ballistics",question:"When setting up to take a shot, why must you NEVER rest the actual barrel of the rifle on a hard surface?",options:["It will scratch the barrel","Resting the barrel alters its natural harmonics during firing, causing the bullet to strike erratically and usually significantly higher","It makes the rifle too loud","It increases recoil"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Rifle barrels whip and vibrate when fired. If the barrel touches a hard surface, these harmonics are interrupted, throwing the shot off target. Always rest the stock, not the barrel."},
  {category:"Ballistics",question:"If a stalker shoots at a deer at a steep 45-degree uphill angle, where should they aim to compensate for gravity?",options:["Higher than normal","Slightly lower than normal","Exactly the same as flat ground","Aim for the neck"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Gravity only affects the true horizontal distance the bullet travels. When shooting at steep upward or downward angles, the horizontal distance is shorter, so the bullet hits high. You must aim slightly low."},
  {category:"Ballistics",question:"What does the term 'trajectory' refer to in rifle shooting?",options:["The speed of the bullet","The curved flight path of the bullet as it drops over distance due to gravity","The expansion of the bullet in the target","The spin imparted by the rifling"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"A bullet does not travel in a straight line; gravity pulls it down as soon as it leaves the muzzle, creating a curved trajectory."},
  {category:"Ballistics",question:"What is the process of 'zeroing' a rifle?",options:["Cleaning the barrel completely","Adjusting the telescopic sights so the bullet's point of impact aligns with the crosshairs at a specific known distance","Emptying the magazine safely","Shooting point-blank into a target"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Zeroing matches your line of sight to the bullet's trajectory at a chosen range (e.g., 100 meters)."},
  {category:"Ballistics",question:"How does a strong crosswind affect a bullet's flight?",options:["It pushes the bullet laterally in the direction the wind is blowing (wind drift)","It slows the bullet down, causing it to hit low","It makes the bullet tumble","It speeds the bullet up"],correctIndex:0,explanation:"Wind exerts pressure on the side of the bullet, causing it to drift off the point of aim. A left-to-right wind will push the bullet to the right."},
// --- Additional questions to complete the 300-question bank ---
  {category:"Biology",question:"What is the gestation period of a Roe deer including delayed implantation?",options:["5 months","7 months","Approximately 10 months","12 months"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Although fertilisation occurs in July/August, the embryo does not implant until late December/January. Kids are born in May/June, making the total time from mating approximately 10 months."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"In which months do Roe does typically give birth?",options:["January and February","March and April","May and June","September and October"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Following the July/August rut and delayed implantation, Roe does give birth in May and June. They typically have one to three kids."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"What is the term for the scent glands located in front of a deer's eyes?",options:["Interdigital glands","Metatarsal glands","Pre-orbital glands","Tarsal glands"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Pre-orbital glands sit in front of each eye and are used to deposit scent on branches and twigs for territorial marking."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"How does a male Muntjac differ from a female Muntjac in terms of antlers?",options:["Females have larger antlers","Males grow short, simple, unbranched antlers on long bony pedicles; females have no antlers","Both sexes grow antlers","Neither sex grows antlers"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Male Muntjac grow short, simple spike antlers on unusually long pedicles that extend down the face. Females lack antlers entirely but may have small bony knobs."},
  {category:"Identification",question:"Which deer species is known for continuously moving its jaw even when not eating, due to near-constant rumination?",options:["Red deer","Muntjac","Fallow deer","Chinese Water Deer"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Muntjac are frequently observed ruminating, their jaw moving rhythmically even when standing still, which is a useful identification cue."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"What is the correct term for a young deer of any species in its first year?",options:["Pup","Foal","Fawn, calf, or kid depending on species","Cub"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Terminology varies by species: Red deer young are calves, Roe are kids, Fallow are fawns, and Sika are calves or fawns."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"When does the Red deer rut typically occur in the UK?",options:["June and July","Late September to late October","December and January","March and April"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"The Red deer rut is one of the most dramatic wildlife events in the UK, typically occurring from late September through October."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"What is the approximate shoulder height of a mature Red deer stag?",options:["60 to 70 cm","80 to 90 cm","110 to 140 cm","160 to 180 cm"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Red deer are the UK's largest native land mammal. Mature stags typically stand between 110 and 140 cm at the shoulder."},
  {category:"Identification",question:"Which deer species is most commonly found in dense conifer plantation woodland and scrubby undergrowth in southern England?",options:["Red Deer","Roe Deer","Muntjac","Sika"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Muntjac thrive in dense woodland with thick understorey. Their small size and preference for cover makes them most associated with southern English woodland."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"What do the terms 'slots', 'fewmets', and 'fraying stocks' refer to respectively in deer field sign?",options:["Teeth, horns, and ears","Footprints, droppings, and rubbed/damaged saplings","Eyes, nose, and antlers","Antlers, rump patches, and glands"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"These are traditional stalking terms: slots are footprints, fewmets are droppings, and fraying stocks are the saplings or posts that deer have rubbed their antlers against."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"What is the minimum age to hold a Firearms Certificate (FAC) in the UK?",options:["14","17","18","21"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"You must be 18 or over to hold a Firearm Certificate in your own name in the UK."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"Under what circumstances can a police officer revoke a Firearms Certificate?",options:["If you move house","If they consider that the holder cannot be permitted to possess a firearm without danger to public safety or the peace","If you change your stalking ground","If you fail to attend a training course"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Police can revoke an FAC if they believe the holder poses a risk to public safety, has been convicted of a relevant offence, or can no longer be trusted with firearms."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"What does Section 19 of the Firearms Act 1968 prohibit?",options:["Owning more than one rifle","Carrying a loaded firearm in a public place without lawful authority or reasonable excuse","Buying ammunition online","Transporting firearms across county boundaries"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Section 19 makes it a criminal offence to carry a loaded firearm in a public place without lawful authority or a reasonable excuse."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"In Scotland, what is the minimum legal muzzle energy to shoot Roe deer?",options:["750 ft/lbs","1,000 ft/lbs","1,500 ft/lbs","1,750 ft/lbs"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Scottish legislation specifies 1,000 ft/lbs of muzzle energy as the minimum for Roe deer, alongside a 50-grain bullet and 2,450 fps velocity."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"What does the Deer (Scotland) Act 1996 require deer management groups to produce?",options:["Annual hunting reports","Deer Management Plans","Veterinary certificates","Police disclosures"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Deer Management Groups in Scotland are required to produce Deer Management Plans showing how they intend to manage deer populations sustainably across a landscape scale."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"Under English law, when must you report the killing or taking of a deer?",options:["You must always report it to the police","Only when using an estate rifle","You are not legally required to report individual cull events; however, records are required for commercial venison sales","Only during the closed season"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"There is no general legal requirement to report culling of deer in England, but anyone selling venison commercially must maintain appropriate records and meet food hygiene requirements."},
  {category:"Safety",question:"What is the maximum safe angle below which you should NEVER shoot at a deer on a slope?",options:["There is no angle restriction","You must always ensure a safe backstop regardless of angle; there is no specific angle limit but you must be certain the bullet will be safely stopped","Anything steeper than 30 degrees is illegal","You can never shoot on a slope"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"There is no specific legal angle restriction, but the principle is absolute: regardless of angle, you must be completely certain the bullet will be safely stopped by a backstop."},
  {category:"Safety",question:"Why is it dangerous to leave a loaded rifle unattended in a high seat?",options:["The scope may fog up","A member of the public or child could find and discharge it, causing serious injury or death","The weather will damage the rifle","Animals could knock it over"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"A loaded, unattended firearm poses an extreme public safety risk. A rifle must never be left loaded, especially in a location accessible to the public."},
  {category:"Safety",question:"What is the recommended practice when loading a cartridge into the chamber?",options:["Load immediately on arrival at the high seat","Only chamber a round when you are in position and there is a realistic chance of a safe, ethical shot","Load while walking to the seat for convenience","Always keep the rifle loaded throughout the stalk"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"A round should only be chambered when you are in a safe, stable shooting position and a deer is present. The chamber should be empty at all other times."},
  {category:"Safety",question:"What is the safest action when you are not planning to shoot for an extended period in a high seat?",options:["Leave the round chambered but apply the safety","Remove the magazine but leave one round in the chamber","Unload the rifle completely, open the bolt and visually check the chamber is empty","Just lower the rifle safely"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"The only guaranteed safe state for a rifle is completely unloaded with the chamber visually confirmed clear."},
  {category:"Ballistics",question:"What is meant by 'bullet drop' in rifle shooting?",options:["When the bullet falls out of the cartridge","The vertical distance the bullet falls below the line of bore over a given range, due to the constant downward acceleration of gravity","The loss of bullet weight on impact","The drop in muzzle velocity"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Gravity constantly accelerates the bullet downward from the moment it leaves the muzzle. The further it travels, the more it drops below the line of bore."},
  {category:"Ballistics",question:"Why do heavier bullets generally retain their velocity better over long distances than lighter bullets of the same calibre?",options:["Because they are fired at higher pressures","Because they have a higher ballistic coefficient, meaning they are more resistant to drag and wind","Because they are made of denser materials","Because they spin faster"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Heavier bullets generally have higher ballistic coefficients, making them more aerodynamically efficient and better at resisting air drag over distance."},
  {category:"Ballistics",question:"What is the effect of altitude on a bullet's trajectory compared to sea level?",options:["Bullets drop more at altitude","Bullets travel in exactly the same path at all altitudes","Bullets drop less at altitude because the air is thinner and there is less drag","Altitude has no effect"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"At higher altitudes the air is thinner, producing less drag on the bullet. As a result, bullets retain velocity better and drop slightly less than at sea level."},
  {category:"Ballistics",question:"What does 'muzzle energy' measure?",options:["How loud the rifle is at the muzzle","The kinetic energy of the bullet as it leaves the barrel, calculated from its weight and velocity","The pressure inside the barrel","The recoil force against the shooter's shoulder"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Muzzle energy (measured in foot-pounds or joules) is the kinetic energy of the bullet at the muzzle, derived from its mass and velocity. It is a key indicator of terminal performance."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"What is the correct process for 'dressing' a deer carcass for the larder?",options:["Skinning it and removing the head only","Removing the skin, head, lower legs, and all internal organs to leave a clean carcase ready for hanging or butchery","Washing it in a stream and hanging it immediately","Only removing the digestive organs in the field"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Full larder dressing involves removing the skin, head, lower legs and feet, and all remaining organs to produce a clean, presentable carcass ready for inspection, hanging, and butchery."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"What is the purpose of 'hanging' a deer carcass in a cool larder after dressing?",options:["To allow the rigor mortis to pass and enzymes to tenderize the meat through controlled aging","To dry it out for preservation","To allow remaining blood to drip out","To cool it quickly"],correctIndex:0,explanation:"Hanging (aging) allows muscle enzymes to break down connective tissue, tenderizing the meat and developing flavour. Proper cooling during this process prevents spoilage."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"What is the minimum recommended larder temperature for safely storing a deer carcass?",options:["Below 7°C","Below 10°C","Below 15°C","Below 20°C"],correctIndex:0,explanation:"Carcasses must be stored below 7°C to prevent bacterial growth. Regular thermometer checks are essential to ensure food safety compliance."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"You observe that a live deer has swollen joints, hair loss, and crusty skin lesions. What should you suspect?",options:["Normal winter coat change","Bluetongue virus or sarcoptic mange, requiring welfare assessment and likely culling","A minor scratch","Excessive rubbing from antler fraying"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"These symptoms suggest parasitic or viral disease. The animal should be culled on welfare grounds, the carcass not used for food, and if Bluetongue is suspected, the APHA must be notified."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"What is the significance of inspecting the mesenteric lymph nodes during the gralloch?",options:["They indicate the deer's age","They are a key site for detecting tuberculosis and other intestinal diseases that indicate the carcass may be unfit for human consumption","They show how much the deer weighed","They determine if the deer was pregnant"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"The mesenteric nodes filter lymph from the gut. Swelling, pus, or calcification here can indicate tuberculosis or other gut-related diseases."},
  {category:"Identification",question:"What is the approximate body weight of a mature Roe buck?",options:["5 to 10 kg","10 to 15 kg","15 to 30 kg","30 to 50 kg"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"A mature Roe buck typically weighs between 15 and 30 kg live weight, with does being slightly smaller."},
  {category:"Identification",question:"Which deer species produces a distinctive whistling alarm call that can be confused with that of a small mammal?",options:["Muntjac","Chinese Water Deer","Roe Deer","Fallow"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Roe deer produce a sharp, whistling bark when alarmed, often causing confusion with the calls of other woodland creatures."},
  {category:"Identification",question:"Which UK deer species has the widest distribution, being found across nearly every county in England?",options:["Red Deer","Sika","Muntjac","Fallow"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Muntjac have rapidly expanded from their original introduction at Woburn to now occupy virtually every county in England, making them one of the most widespread deer species."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"What is the correct term for the rounded, flattened antler section unique to mature Fallow bucks?",options:["The crown","The tine","The palm or shovel","The pedicle"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"The broad, flat section of a mature Fallow buck's antler is called the palm or shovel. It is what gives Fallow antlers their distinctive palmate appearance."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"Deer are considered prey animals. How does this shape their sensory system?",options:["They have poor vision but excellent hearing only","They have eyes positioned on the sides of their head giving near 300-degree vision, acute hearing, and a highly developed sense of smell","They rely only on smell","They have forward-facing eyes for binocular vision like predators"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"As prey animals, deer have evolved wide-field vision to detect movement from almost any direction, combined with large mobile ears and an exceptional sense of smell to detect danger."},
  {category:"Fieldcraft",question:"What is the recommended approach angle when following up a wounded deer?",options:["Always approach from directly downwind","Follow the blood trail calmly and methodically, pausing frequently to listen for movement or disturbance","Run directly to where the deer was last seen","Follow the deer's exact tracks"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"A methodical, quiet approach keeps the wounded animal from being pushed further. Pausing to listen often reveals where the deer has bedded."},
  {category:"Fieldcraft",question:"When blood trailing a wounded deer, what does a sudden stop in the blood trail usually indicate?",options:["The deer has recovered and run away","The deer may have bedded nearby; approach very slowly and silently","The deer has entered water","The blood trail has been washed away"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"A sudden end to a blood trail often means the deer has lain down nearby. Pushing forward noisily risks jumping the deer up again; approach with extreme caution."},
  {category:"Fieldcraft",question:"Why should a stalker always mark the exact spot where the deer was standing when it was shot?",options:["To map the estate","So they can find their way back in the dark","To establish a reference point for reading sign (hair, blood, bone) and beginning an accurate blood trail","To comply with legislation"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"The exact shot site is the starting point for all follow-up work. Marking it with a natural feature or stick ensures you can accurately read the sign and track effectively."},
  {category:"Fieldcraft",question:"In what conditions should you consider using a tracking dog to recover a wounded deer?",options:["Only on dry days","Whenever there is any doubt about the deer's recovery, particularly with gut shots, poor blood trails, or when the deer has been lost in dense cover","Only after waiting 24 hours","Only if the weather is below 5 degrees"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"A trained tracking dog (Bluthund or similar) dramatically improves recovery rates for difficult tracking scenarios, reducing the risk of a wounded animal being lost."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"What is the primary diet of deer in the UK?",options:["Insects and small mammals","Grass, herbs, leaves, shoots, bark, fungi, and agricultural crops","Only bark and tree roots","Only aquatic vegetation"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"UK deer are herbivores with a varied diet including grasses, dwarf shrubs, herbs, tree leaves, shoots, bark, fungi, and agricultural crops."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"What sensory advantage does a deer's moist nose provide?",options:["Better hearing","Improved eyesight","It dissolves scent particles from the air more efficiently, greatly enhancing their sense of smell","It helps them find underground water"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"A deer's moist nose functions like a wet sponge, capturing and dissolving scent molecules from the air, making their olfactory sense extraordinarily sensitive."},
  {category:"Identification",question:"How does the summer coat of a Red deer differ from its winter coat in terms of colour and texture?",options:["Summer is dark brown and thick; winter is bright red and thin","Summer is bright chestnut or reddish-brown and short; winter is darker grey-brown and much thicker","There is no colour difference","Summer coat is spotted; winter coat is plain"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Red deer are a rich chestnut-red in summer, which is how they got their name. Their winter coat is a darker, thicker grey-brown to cope with cold conditions."},
  {category:"Safety",question:"What is a 'double feed' malfunction in a semi-automatic or magazine-fed rifle?",options:["Loading two magazines simultaneously","When a spent case fails to eject and a new round attempts to chamber on top of it, causing a serious jam requiring clearing","Accidentally firing two rounds","Loading the magazine incorrectly"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"A double feed is a common malfunction where a spent case stovepipes or fails to extract, and the next round jams against it. The safe procedure is to remove the magazine, lock the bolt back, and clear the chamber."},
  {category:"Ballistics",question:"What effect does barrel fouling (build-up of copper or carbon deposits) have on accuracy?",options:["It improves accuracy by filling barrel imperfections","It has no effect on accuracy","Over time it degrades accuracy as it changes the internal dimensions and surface of the bore","It only affects the sound of the shot"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Carbon and copper fouling gradually builds up in the barrel, changing its internal dimensions and affecting how the bullet engages the rifling, leading to degraded accuracy."},
  {category:"Ballistics",question:"What is the purpose of a rifle's 'rifling' (the spiral grooves cut into the barrel)?",options:["To make the bullet travel faster","To impart spin on the bullet, stabilizing it in flight and improving accuracy","To reduce barrel pressure","To make the bullet expand on impact"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Rifling imparts a stabilising spin to the bullet as it passes down the barrel. This gyroscopic effect keeps the bullet flying point-forward and dramatically improves accuracy."},
  {category:"Disease & Management",question:"What is Chronic Wasting Disease (CWD) and why is it considered a major threat?",options:["A minor skin condition curable with antibiotics","A fatal prion disease affecting the nervous system of deer that has been identified in Europe and poses a catastrophic threat to wild deer populations","A type of liver fluke","A seasonal hormonal imbalance"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"CWD is a fatal, transmissible prion disease similar to BSE in cattle. It causes progressive neurological degeneration, is 100% fatal, and has no cure. Its spread in Europe is monitored extremely closely."},
  {category:"Disease & Management",question:"What is the correct management response if you discover a deer with suspected Bovine Tuberculosis?",options:["Shoot it and sell it normally","Do not move the carcass; notify the Animal and Plant Health Agency (APHA) immediately; the carcass must be tested and disposed of appropriately","Shoot it and bury it deep on the estate","Leave it alive and monitor it"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Bovine TB is a Notifiable Disease. The carcass must be preserved in place and the APHA contacted. Unauthorized disposal of a TB-suspect carcass is a serious offence."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"What is the legal position on using a rifle with a sound moderator for deer stalking?",options:["It is illegal to use a moderator without a police permit","It is perfectly legal, and moderators are encouraged by stalking bodies as they protect the shooter's hearing and reduce disturbance to livestock","Moderators are banned on public land","You need a separate certificate entry for the moderator"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Sound moderators are entirely legal and are actively encouraged for deer stalking in the UK. A moderator does require its own entry on your Firearms Certificate as it is a firearm component."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"Under the Deer Act 1991, what is the specific offence of taking or killing a deer using a trap or snare?",options:["It is a civil matter only","It is a strict criminal offence carrying a fine and/or imprisonment","It is legal if on private land","It is only illegal during the closed season"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"The Deer Act explicitly prohibits the use of any trap, snare, or net to take or kill deer. This is a criminal offence under the Act."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"What is the correct term for the period immediately after a deer has fed when it moves to a safe, secluded spot to lie down and chew the cud?",options:["Resting","Ruminating or lying-up","Wallowing","Fraying"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"After feeding, deer move to cover where they feel safe to lie down and ruminate (chew the cud). This period of lying-up can last several hours."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"What is the correct term for the permanent shed skin from a deer's antler?",options:["Velvet","\'Fraying\'","Cast velvet","Kemp"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"The skin shed from antlers is called cast velvet (once it has dried and been rubbed off). While still living on the growing antler, it is simply called velvet."},
  {category:"Identification",question:"Chinese Water Deer are sometimes confused with Muntjac. What key difference helps separate the two species?",options:["CWD are much larger than Muntjac","CWD lack the hunched posture of Muntjac; they stand upright and level, have rounder ears, and the males have visible tusks but no antlers","CWD have palmate antlers","CWD always have spots"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"CWD have an upright, level body posture unlike the hunched Muntjac. Their very large, rounded ears and visible tusks (in males) are key differentiating features."},
  {category:"Safety",question:"When should you engage the safety catch on a rifle?",options:["Only when loading","As a supplement to safe muzzle direction and unloading — never as the primary or sole safety measure","Continuously during the stalk","Only when sighting in at the range"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"The safety catch is a secondary safety measure. Primary safety is always a safe muzzle direction and an unloaded chamber. The safety catch should be on whenever appropriate but never relied upon alone."},
  {category:"Fieldcraft",question:"What does a 'roebuck territory' typically consist of?",options:["A vast open hillside","A defined area of woodland or scrub, marked with scent from glands and fraying, which the buck actively defends from rival males","A shared grazing area with other bucks","Only the immediate surroundings of the doe"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Roe bucks are highly territorial, maintaining and defending a defined home range using scent marking, fraying, and physical confrontation during the rut."},
  {category:"Fieldcraft",question:"Why is dawn and dusk considered the best time for deer stalking?",options:["The light is better for photography","Deer are most active at these times (crepuscular behaviour) as they move between resting and feeding areas","The wind is always favourable at dawn and dusk","It is easier to use a high seat in low light"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Deer are crepuscular, meaning they are most active at dawn and dusk. These are the prime periods when deer are on the move between cover and feeding areas."},
  {category:"Fieldcraft",question:"What is the purpose of using binoculars before a shot, not just a rifle scope?",options:["Binoculars provide better magnification","Using a rifle scope to observe deer (rather than shooting) is dangerous and unethical as it means pointing a loaded weapon at animals and people; binoculars allow safe, prolonged observation","Binoculars are cheaper","Scopes fog up too easily"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Pointing a loaded rifle at anything you do not intend to shoot is a fundamental safety violation. Binoculars are always used to observe, identify, and assess deer before the rifle is raised."},
  {category:"Fieldcraft",question:"When should you shoot a deer from a high seat versus a ground stalk?",options:["High seats are always preferable","The decision depends on the management situation; high seats offer a stable platform and elevated angle for clear backstops, while ground stalking allows coverage of larger areas","Ground stalking is always safer","High seats should only be used at night"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Both methods have their place. High seats give excellent sight lines, stable shooting positions, and often a safe downward-angled backstop. Ground stalking is more versatile for covering ground."},
{category:"Biology",question:"What is the collective term for a group of Roe deer?",options:["A herd","A bevy","A parcel","A sounder"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"A group of Roe deer is traditionally called a bevy. Red and Fallow deer form herds; Fallow are sometimes called a parcel."},
  {category:"Identification",question:"What is the average shoulder height of a mature Muntjac?",options:["30 to 35 cm","45 to 52 cm","65 to 75 cm","80 to 90 cm"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Muntjac typically stand 45 to 52 cm at the shoulder, making them the smallest deer species in the UK."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"At what age do Roe deer kids typically become independent from their mother?",options:["2 to 3 weeks","2 to 3 months","Around 10 to 12 months","At 2 years old"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Roe kids remain with their mother through their first winter, dispersing as yearlings in the spring, typically around 10 to 12 months old."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"In England and Wales, what is the open season for Sika Hinds?",options:["1st August to 30th April","1st April to 31st October","1st November to 31st March","There is no closed season"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Sika Hinds, like Red Hinds and Fallow Does, are in season from 1st November to 31st March in England and Wales."},
  {category:"Safety",question:"What is the correct action when a guest or inexperienced person on a stalk drops their rifle?",options:["Leave it for them to retrieve","Pick it up immediately for them","Immediately make the rifle safe — remove the magazine and open the bolt to visually check the chamber is empty","Only check if it went off"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Any dropped firearm must be treated as potentially unsafe. The chamber must be visually confirmed clear before the rifle is used again."},
  {category:"Meat Hygiene",question:"What does 'rigor mortis' mean and why is it relevant to venison handling?",options:["A disease of deer muscles","The temporary stiffening of muscles after death, caused by chemical changes; meat should not be aggressively chilled during this period to avoid cold shortening","A method of aging meat","The final stages of the gralloch"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Rigor mortis is the temporary rigidity of muscles following death. Aggressively chilling a carcass during rigor can cause cold shortening, toughening the meat permanently."},
  {category:"Fieldcraft",question:"What is the main danger of shooting at a running deer?",options:["The deer may escape","The shot is likely to be inaccurate and may result in a wounding shot rather than a clean kill","The deer will alarm other deer","Running deer are outside the law"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Shooting at moving targets significantly increases the risk of a poor shot placement, causing a wounding injury rather than an instant, humane death. Only take shots at stationary or very slow-moving deer."},
  {category:"Biology",question:"What is the approximate lifespan of a wild Roe deer in the UK?",options:["3 to 5 years","7 to 10 years","12 to 15 years","20 to 25 years"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Wild Roe deer typically live 7 to 10 years, with some reaching 12 years or more in favourable conditions. Tooth wear, predation, disease, and road casualties all limit lifespan."},
  {category:"Identification",question:"Which feature most reliably distinguishes a Sika deer from a Red deer at a distance in summer?",options:["Sika are always larger","Sika have a clearly defined white heart-shaped rump patch with a black upper border, visible spots in summer coat, and a shorter neck","Red deer have no rump patch","Red deer have palmate antlers"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"The white heart-shaped rump with black border is the most reliable field identifier for Sika. In summer, many Sika also retain obvious white spots."},
  {category:"Legislation",question:"What is the legal position on selling venison from a deer you have shot?",options:["You can sell it freely to anyone","You can only give it away; it cannot be sold","To sell venison commercially it must generally be processed through an AGHE or sold under the Primary Producer exemption to local consumers or local retailers","You need a special game dealer licence to sell any venison"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Commercial venison sales require food hygiene compliance. The main routes are through an AGHE or under the Primary Producer exemption for small quantities sold locally."},
  {category:"Disease & Management",question:"What action should you take if you see deer showing signs of severe emaciation, trembling, excessive salivation, or unusual behaviour?",options:["Leave them alone as they will recover","Shoot all affected deer immediately and sell the carcasses","Cull affected individuals on welfare grounds, do not move or sell carcasses, and contact the APHA if a Notifiable Disease is suspected","Monitor from a distance and report to the BDS"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Severely ill deer should be culled on welfare grounds. Carcasses must not enter the food chain, and any suspicion of a Notifiable Disease must be reported to the APHA immediately."}
,
// ── DISEASE & MANAGEMENT (Q301 - Q330) ──
  {category:"Disease & Management",question:"What is the primary route of transmission of Bovine Tuberculosis (bTB) between deer and cattle?",options:["Contaminated water alone","Inhalation of respiratory droplets or contact with infected saliva, urine, and faeces from infected animals","Only through biting insects","Purely through contaminated soil"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"bTB is primarily spread by close contact and inhalation of infected aerosols. Deer and cattle sharing grazing land or fence lines are at risk of cross-species transmission."},
  {category:"Disease & Management",question:"What is the clinical significance of finding multiple, enlarged, and fused lymph nodes in a deer carcass during inspection?",options:["It is a normal finding in older deer","It indicates active or past infection, potentially including tuberculosis, requiring the carcass to be condemned and authorities notified if TB is suspected","It simply means the deer was well-fed","It is only significant in male deer"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Enlarged, coalesced lymph nodes are a key indicator of systemic disease. TB causes characteristic caseous or calcified lesions within nodes. Any such finding warrants carcass condemnation."},
  {category:"Disease & Management",question:"Which external parasite causes 'mange' in deer, resulting in hair loss, thickened skin, and intense irritation?",options:["Liver fluke","Lungworm","Sarcoptic mite (Sarcoptes scabiei)","Sheep tick"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Sarcoptic mange is caused by microscopic mites burrowing into the skin. It causes severe itching, hair loss, and skin thickening and can be fatal in severe cases."},
  {category:"Disease & Management",question:"What condition is caused by the parasite Elaphostrongylus cervi in deer?",options:["Liver fluke","Elaphostrongylosis, a muscular worm infection affecting muscles and the nervous system","A type of tapeworm","Warble fly infestation"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Elaphostrongylus cervi is a nematode worm that inhabits the muscles, connective tissue, and central nervous system of red and sika deer, transmitted by slugs and snails as intermediate hosts."},
  {category:"Disease & Management",question:"What is the life cycle of the liver fluke (Fasciola hepatica) relevant to deer management?",options:["It is transmitted directly between deer","It requires an intermediate host — the mud snail (Galba truncatula) — found in wet, boggy ground","It is airborne between animals","It is only transmitted through contaminated feed"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"The liver fluke requires the mud snail as an intermediate host. Deer grazing wet, rush-covered or boggy pastures are particularly at risk of acquiring the infection."},
  {category:"Disease & Management",question:"You shoot a deer and on gralloching find the lungs are heavily consolidated (solid, airless, dark) with large areas of pneumonia. What should you do with the carcass?",options:["Trim away the lungs and sell the rest normally","Condemn the carcass — do not allow it to enter the food chain; seek veterinary advice if a Notifiable Disease is suspected","The meat is fine as cooking will kill any bacteria","Only notify the APHA if the deer showed neurological signs"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Severe, extensive pneumonia renders a carcass unfit for human consumption. The cause may be bacterial or viral; the carcass must be condemned and, if a notifiable condition is possible, the APHA must be informed."},
  {category:"Disease & Management",question:"What does the term 'zoonosis' (or 'zoonotic disease') mean in the context of deer disease?",options:["A disease only found in zoo animals","An infection transmissible between deer and humans","A disease only affecting male deer","A disease transmitted by insects only"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"A zoonosis is a disease that can be transmitted from animals to humans. Relevant examples for deer stalkers include Lyme disease, leptospirosis, and — potentially — bovine tuberculosis."},
  {category:"Disease & Management",question:"What is the purpose of the 'Deer Management Group' (DMG) system in Scotland?",options:["To set trophy prices for stalked deer","To enable neighbouring landowners and land managers to coordinate deer management across property boundaries at a landscape scale","To control the sale of venison nationally","To regulate firearms licensing for deer stalking"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"DMGs allow collective management of deer across multiple estates, enabling population control and habitat management to be coordinated effectively at a scale that individual properties cannot achieve alone."},
  {category:"Disease & Management",question:"Why is it important to record the locations where deer are culled on an estate?",options:["It is a legal requirement under the Deer Act","To build a long-term picture of deer movement, habitat use, and population distribution, helping to target future management effort effectively","Only required for bucks, not does","Only relevant when selling venison commercially"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Spatial cull records allow stalkers and managers to identify key deer movement routes, feeding areas, and refuges. Over time they build an invaluable evidence base for adaptive deer management."},
  {category:"Disease & Management",question:"What does a 'cull plan' aim to achieve in deer population management?",options:["To kill as many deer as possible each season","To set species-specific and sex-specific targets that maintain the deer population at a level compatible with the habitat and land use objectives","To record trophy quality","To determine venison prices for the season"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"A cull plan uses population surveys, habitat assessment, and damage data to set evidence-based targets for the number of males and females of each species to be culled, achieving a sustainable population."},
  {category:"Disease & Management",question:"What is the key principle of 'selective culling' in deer management?",options:["Culling only the largest and heaviest animals for maximum venison yield","Prioritising the removal of animals that are old, injured, diseased, or poor quality, to improve the health and productivity of the remaining population","Culling all animals of a particular age class","Culling randomly without selection criteria"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Selective culling removes animals that are a drain on the population — the sick, injured, malformed, or very old — leaving healthy, productive individuals to sustain the herd."},
  {category:"Disease & Management",question:"What is the significance of the sex ratio in a managed deer population?",options:["Sex ratio has no management significance","A balanced or slightly female-biased sex ratio generally produces the healthiest, most productive population. Excess males create competition without proportionally increasing recruitment","More males always means better genetics","Only the total number matters, not the sex ratio"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"In most deer management contexts, a ratio of roughly one male to two or three females optimises recruitment while maintaining natural rutting behaviour. Heavily skewed ratios reduce overall population productivity."},
  {category:"Disease & Management",question:"What are the key signs of a deer suffering from advanced Chronic Wasting Disease (CWD)?",options:["Bright eyes, alert behaviour, and normal movement","Dramatic weight loss, behavioural changes such as loss of fear of humans, excessive salivation, difficulty swallowing, abnormal gait, and ultimately death","Mild lethargy and slightly dull coat","Only visible internal changes at post-mortem"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"CWD is a prion disease that progressively destroys the brain and nervous system. Clinical signs develop slowly over months and are invariably fatal with no treatment or cure."},
  {category:"Disease & Management",question:"Why is Chronic Wasting Disease (CWD) considered a major biosecurity concern in Europe?",options:["Because it can be cured easily if caught early","Because it is a 100% fatal prion disease with no cure, capable of spreading rapidly through wild deer populations, and has already been detected in Norway, Finland, Sweden and other European countries","Because it only affects farmed deer","Because it is the same as BSE in cattle"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"CWD has no cure or vaccine. It persists in the environment for years via infected soil and vegetation. Its detection in wild European deer populations represents an ongoing and serious biosecurity threat."},
  {category:"Disease & Management",question:"What action should a stalker take if they observe a deer that is uncharacteristically approachable, appearing confused or disorientated?",options:["Approach it and attempt to capture it for a vet","Photograph it and post on social media","Do not approach; note the location, observe from a safe distance, report to the relevant authority (e.g., APHA, NatureScot, or NE) and cull the animal safely if appropriate","Leave it; it will recover on its own"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"An abnormally tame or disorientated deer may have severe disease including CWD or neurological illness. It should not be approached unnecessarily; authorities should be alerted and the animal culled if safe to do so."},
  {category:"Disease & Management",question:"What does a high density of deer in a woodland ecosystem typically lead to over time?",options:["Improved woodland biodiversity due to grazing","Increased tree growth through nutrient cycling from dung","Severe suppression of ground flora, tree regeneration failure, loss of woodland structure, and reduction in invertebrate and bird diversity","No significant ecological change"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"Excessive deer numbers prevent woodland regeneration (no young trees can survive browsing), eliminate ground flora, and reduce the structural diversity on which many woodland species depend."},
  {category:"Disease & Management",question:"What is 'population monitoring' and why is it essential for effective deer management?",options:["Counting deer only once every ten years","Regular assessment of deer numbers, distribution, sex ratios, age structure, and condition through methods such as dusk/dawn counts, thermal imaging, trail cameras, or driven surveys, to inform adaptive management","Only required on large estates over 5,000 acres","Monitoring is optional and only helps with venison pricing"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Without regular population data, managers cannot know whether their cull is having the intended effect. Monitoring allows targets to be adjusted annually in response to actual population trends."},
  {category:"Disease & Management",question:"What welfare obligation does a deer manager have towards a deer that has been injured but not killed by a shot?",options:["They can leave it if they believe it will recover","They have a legal and ethical obligation to make every reasonable effort to find and humanely dispatch the wounded animal as quickly as possible","They must only wait 24 hours before giving up the search","They must notify the police within one hour"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Under animal welfare legislation and stalking ethics, a wounded animal must be followed up immediately and dispatched as quickly as possible to minimise suffering."},
  {category:"Disease & Management",question:"What is the function of the 'pre-rut' period in male deer behaviour?",options:["Males feed intensively and build fat reserves","Males become inactive and avoid females","Males begin to increase territorial behaviour, sparring with rivals, and increasingly interacting with females in preparation for the main rut","Males abandon their territories entirely"],correctIndex:2,explanation:"In the pre-rut period, testosterone is rising and males become increasingly competitive. They establish territories, spar with rivals, and begin to attend females before the peak of the rut."},
  {category:"Disease & Management",question:"What is the recommended minimum information that should be recorded for each deer culled?",options:["Species and sex only","Date, location (grid reference or map pin), species, sex, age class, weight, shot details, and any abnormalities observed during gralloch","Only the venison weight","Species and the name of the stalker"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Comprehensive cull records are the foundation of evidence-based deer management. This data feeds into population models, habitat assessment, and venison traceability requirements."},
  {category:"Disease & Management",question:"Why is the age structure of a culled sample important to assess?",options:["It has no management value","It allows the manager to assess whether the population is increasing (many juveniles), stable, or declining (few juveniles), and whether the cull is achieving its objectives","Age structure only matters for trophy deer","Age structure is only relevant to Red deer"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"A population with many juvenile deer is growing; one dominated by older animals may be stable or declining. Age structure data from the cull helps validate population estimates."},
  {category:"Disease & Management",question:"What is 'leptospirosis' and how is it relevant to deer stalkers?",options:["A tick-borne disease exclusively affecting deer","A bacterial infection (Leptospira spp.) carried by deer and other wildlife, transmissible to humans through contact with infected urine or contaminated water — particularly a risk during the gralloch","A viral infection only transmissible by insects","A plant toxin that affects deer grazing lowland pastures"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Deer can carry Leptospira bacteria in their kidneys and urinary tract. Contact with infected urine — particularly during gralloching — can cause serious illness in humans. Gloves must always be worn."},
  {category:"Disease & Management",question:"During an estate deer count, what does a consistently poor body condition score across the population suggest?",options:["The population is in excellent health","The population is likely exceeding the carrying capacity of the habitat — more deer than the land can support — requiring an increased cull effort","Poor body condition only affects venison quality, not management decisions","Body condition has no bearing on population management"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Widespread poor body condition indicates competition for food, meaning the population exceeds the land's carrying capacity. An increased cull is required to restore balance between deer numbers and habitat quality."},
  {category:"Disease & Management",question:"What is the ecological rationale for culling female deer (hinds, does) at higher numbers than males during population reduction programmes?",options:["Females are easier to shoot","Because each female represents future recruitment potential; removing females reduces the birth rate and thus population growth far more effectively than removing equivalent numbers of males","Males are protected by law during reductions","Females produce lower quality venison so are less valuable commercially"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Population growth is driven by the number of breeding females. Removing one female eliminates her and all her future offspring. Removing males generally has little effect on the rate of population increase."},
  {category:"Disease & Management",question:"What are the visible signs of 'keds' (deer keds, Lipoptena cervi) on a deer carcass?",options:["Swollen lymph nodes","Small, flat, wingless flies found on the skin and in the coat, often visible when the coat is parted","Holes in the hide from larvae","Blistering around the mouth"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Deer keds are ectoparasites that live in the coat of deer. They are flat, wingless flies that drop their wings after finding a host. They can bite humans and are found throughout the coat."},
  {category:"Disease & Management",question:"What is the significance of finding lungworms (Dictyocaulus spp.) in the airways during carcass inspection?",options:["They are always fatal and the carcass must be condemned","Mild infestations may be an incidental finding; heavy burdens indicate poor health, reduce the deer's resilience, and the affected lungs should be condemned but the carcass may be salvageable","Lungworms indicate the deer was drinking from contaminated water and is of no management significance","Lungworms are only found in farmed deer"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Lungworms are common in deer. Light infections may be subclinical, but heavy infestations cause significant lung damage and respiratory distress. Affected lungs must be discarded; the rest of the carcass may be suitable depending on overall condition."},
  {category:"Disease & Management",question:"What is 'population viability' in the context of wild deer management?",options:["The maximum number of deer that can be shot per season","The minimum population size and genetic diversity required for a population to maintain itself long-term without human intervention or becoming inbred","The number of deer needed to support a commercial stalking business","The ratio of deer to available woodland cover"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Population viability analysis assesses whether a population is large and genetically diverse enough to persist over time. Very small, isolated populations are vulnerable to inbreeding, disease events, and random demographic fluctuations."},
  {category:"Disease & Management",question:"Why is it important that deer management plans are reviewed and updated annually?",options:["It is a legal requirement under the Wildlife and Countryside Act","Because deer populations, habitat conditions, and land management objectives change year on year; an annual review ensures the cull targets remain relevant and evidence-based","Annual review is only required for Red deer estates","Only required when venison prices change significantly"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Deer management is adaptive. Annual review of cull records, population data, habitat condition, and land use allows the management plan to be refined in response to what is actually happening on the ground."},
  {category:"Disease & Management",question:"What is the purpose of a 'thermal imaging' survey in deer management?",options:["To identify diseased animals by their body temperature alone","To count deer accurately at night by detecting their heat signature, providing population data that daytime counts often miss due to deer being concealed in cover","To locate wounded deer after a shot","To assess habitat temperature for planting decisions"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Thermal imaging (FLIR) surveys conducted at night reveal deer that are hidden in cover during daylight counts. They provide much more accurate population data, particularly for species like Muntjac and Roe that use dense cover."},
  {category:"Disease & Management",question:"What role do deer play as 'seed dispersers' in woodland ecosystems?",options:["Deer have no role in seed dispersal","Deer spread plant seeds via their coat, hooves, and gut, contributing to woodland plant community composition — though this positive role must be balanced against the damage caused by excessive deer numbers","Deer only spread invasive non-native species","Deer are purely destructive and have no positive ecological role"],correctIndex:1,explanation:"Deer move seeds around in their fur, on their hooves, and in their digestive tract, contributing to natural plant dispersal. This ecological service is positive but can be outweighed by the browsing damage caused by excessive deer populations."}
];
